CATHERINE KAPUTA: --not
even the Google brand.

00:00:03.990 --> 00:00:07.630
And that's a very powerful
brand, as you all know.

00:00:07.630 --> 00:00:10.600
It's one of the most admired
companies in the world,

00:00:10.600 --> 00:00:13.140
voted most innovative company.

00:00:13.140 --> 00:00:15.320
No, we're not going
to talk about Google.

00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:18.840
We're here to talk about the
most important brand you'll

00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:21.600
ever market, brand you.

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:25.060
And virtual branding
and social selling

00:00:25.060 --> 00:00:27.740
is especially
important for sellers,

00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:30.640
for sales professionals
to really understand.

00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:34.290
Because if you don't leverage
it, as powerful as Google is,

00:00:34.290 --> 00:00:38.510
you won't be leveraging things
that your competitors are

00:00:38.510 --> 00:00:39.140
leveraging.

00:00:39.140 --> 00:00:42.530
You won't be leveraging things
that your clients and prospects

00:00:42.530 --> 00:00:43.950
are using.

00:00:43.950 --> 00:00:48.150
So it's important, when
you think about it,

00:00:48.150 --> 00:00:52.510
to build a brand for yourself
online as well as in person.

00:00:52.510 --> 00:00:55.260
Social selling and virtual
branding on LinkedIn

00:00:55.260 --> 00:00:56.600
can help you do that.

00:00:56.600 --> 00:00:59.860
If you want to
expand your network,

00:00:59.860 --> 00:01:04.333
shorten the sales cycle,
LinkedIn can help you do that.

00:01:04.333 --> 00:01:08.340
Before we start, let's look at
an interesting story of a sales

00:01:08.340 --> 00:01:14.360
person who transcended
the old world of selling

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:19.900
and is very successful now
in the new world of selling,

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:22.040
Barbara Corcoran,
who is a salesperson

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:24.709
in a different area than yours.

00:01:24.709 --> 00:01:26.250
And Barbara has an
interesting story.

00:01:26.250 --> 00:01:30.240
She moved to New
York in her late 20s.

00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:34.440
She had 22 different jobs,
cycled through them all, more

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:38.880
than I even had, and started
out, went to New York City,

00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:42.310
and established a real
estate brokerage business

00:01:42.310 --> 00:01:44.620
with her boyfriend.

00:01:44.620 --> 00:01:47.945
And after about six
months, she figured out

00:01:47.945 --> 00:01:51.550
he was having an affair
with his office secretary.

00:01:51.550 --> 00:01:56.660
So she says, I'm out of here,
and they divvy up the assets.

00:01:56.660 --> 00:02:00.840
She gets $1,000, and she
goes to start her own firm.

00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:02.360
As she's leaving,
he goes, you'll

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:04.840
never be able to
make it without me.

00:02:04.840 --> 00:02:08.669
And she starts her own company.

00:02:08.669 --> 00:02:10.600
She calls it the Corcoran Group.

00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:13.460
And at this time, this
was the mid 1980s,

00:02:13.460 --> 00:02:16.820
and it was a time that there
wasn't a lot of information

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:20.320
about residential real
estate prices in New York.

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:27.040
It was a very secretive world,
and it was run by wealthy women

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:30.480
in mink coats that had keys
to all the best apartments

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:32.560
and kept all the
information very secret.

00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:35.890
And so Barbara saw this
hole in the marketplace,

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:38.980
and she thought, I'm
going to fill that hole.

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:44.220
Her new firm, in its first year
it just sold 11 apartments.

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:47.430
So she added up the sales
prices of all 11 apartments,

00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:53.380
divided by 11, and came up with
$242,000 as the average price.

00:02:53.380 --> 00:02:57.630
And she wrote a report that she
called "The Corcoran Report."

00:02:57.630 --> 00:03:02.410
And she made 60 Xerox copies,
sent them to 60 reporters

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:05.230
at "The New York
Times," and it landed

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:08.640
on the front page of the real
estate section of "The New York

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:10.200
Times."

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:14.500
The lead sentence was,
according to Barbara Corcoran,

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:18.750
expert on high-end real estate
in New York, blah, blah, blah.

00:03:18.750 --> 00:03:21.210
So overnight she
went from a nobody

00:03:21.210 --> 00:03:23.310
to somebody that
had a brand, that

00:03:23.310 --> 00:03:30.100
had a visibility
as a strong leader.

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:34.620
Then for her second issue
of "The Corcoran Report,"

00:03:34.620 --> 00:03:38.990
she thought, gee, I'd
like to expand my network.

00:03:38.990 --> 00:03:42.120
I'd like to have wealthy
people endorsing me.

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:46.530
And when you think of a very
famous person in New York

00:03:46.530 --> 00:03:50.440
real estate that you would be
proud to have endorse yourself,

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:52.430
who comes to mind
in the '80s who's

00:03:52.430 --> 00:03:54.194
still very prominent today?

00:03:54.194 --> 00:03:55.110
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:55.985
CATHERINE KAPUTA: OK.

00:03:55.985 --> 00:03:56.814
But also--

00:03:56.814 --> 00:03:57.730
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:57.730 --> 00:03:59.438
CATHERINE KAPUTA: No,
Donald Trump is it.

00:03:59.438 --> 00:04:00.610
Donald Trump is it.

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:04.590
So she wanted Donald
Trump to endorse her.

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:08.970
So she calls his office, and
she says to the secretary,

00:04:08.970 --> 00:04:11.000
I'm doing the second
issue of "The Corcoran

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.620
Report" on the most expensive
residential buildings in New

00:04:14.620 --> 00:04:20.070
York City, and I'd like
to interview Mr. Trump.

00:04:20.070 --> 00:04:23.030
And the secretary
goes, Barbara who?

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:27.660
And she says, well, there was
a feature in "The New York

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:28.160
Times."

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:30.920
So she said, he's very busy.

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:33.660
I really can't set
up an appointment.

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:36.940
And then she said, oh, that's
too bad, because according

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:39.100
to my calculation--
at that time he

00:04:39.100 --> 00:04:42.870
was advertising Trump
Tower in the 1980s,

00:04:42.870 --> 00:04:45.990
and he was advertising it as the
most expensive building in New

00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:52.810
York City-- Trump Tower
is not number one.

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:55.680
She gets a meeting with
Donald Trump telling him

00:04:55.680 --> 00:04:57.130
he's number two.

00:04:57.130 --> 00:04:59.730
So she has the meeting
with Donald Trump,

00:04:59.730 --> 00:05:04.060
and he says to her, here's how
to calculate the average sale

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:04.560
price.

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:06.454
And of course she
knew that there

00:05:06.454 --> 00:05:08.870
were other ways of calculating
it and that by most of them

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:10.410
his building was
the most expensive,

00:05:10.410 --> 00:05:13.370
but she let him convince her.

00:05:13.370 --> 00:05:17.380
And then he said to her
at the end of the meeting,

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:20.250
you know, I'm running a
major ad campaign right now

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:24.320
on Trump Tower, and
I'll put in each ad

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:27.690
that it's the most expensive
residential building according

00:05:27.690 --> 00:05:30.320
to "The Corcoran Report."

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:33.710
So then she became
even more successful

00:05:33.710 --> 00:05:36.750
because she had Donald
Trump's endorsement.

00:05:36.750 --> 00:05:39.440
So one of the things that I
want to leave you with this

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:43.570
you want to attach
an idea to yourself.

00:05:43.570 --> 00:05:45.650
My first rule of
branding is you want

00:05:45.650 --> 00:05:48.020
to attach an idea to yourself.

00:05:48.020 --> 00:05:53.205
Barbara attached an idea that
she was a real estate expert.

00:05:53.205 --> 00:05:54.790
And she had very
little experience,

00:05:54.790 --> 00:05:57.410
but she attached
that idea to herself.

00:05:57.410 --> 00:05:59.900
It was a different idea,
because at that time

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:02.880
no one was filling that
place in the marketplace.

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:04.640
So you want to attach
a different idea.

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:08.740
In a sea of goldfish, you
want to be a green fish.

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:10.530
You want to attach
an idea that's

00:06:10.530 --> 00:06:13.840
authentic, that's something
that's true to you.

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:15.480
And you want to
attach an idea that's

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:19.076
relevant to the marketplace.

00:06:19.076 --> 00:06:20.700
Anyway, here's my
Donald Trump picture.

00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:23.150
This is Donald Trump's
reaction when he found out

00:06:23.150 --> 00:06:27.720
that he wasn't going to be
the number one building.

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:30.220
And so he ran this ad
campaign, the most expensive

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:33.140
residential building
in New York City,

00:06:33.140 --> 00:06:36.350
which leads me to my
second rule of branding.

00:06:36.350 --> 00:06:37.400
You want to network.

00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:40.900
You want to network
for influential people.

00:06:40.900 --> 00:06:43.160
Marketers always
know the best way

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:48.460
to sell yourself is to get
other people to do it for you.

00:06:48.460 --> 00:06:52.260
Then in the mid 1990s
during another slump

00:06:52.260 --> 00:06:55.230
in the real estate
market in New York,

00:06:55.230 --> 00:06:57.310
Barbara Corcoran
read that Madonna

00:06:57.310 --> 00:07:00.710
was looking for an
apartment in Manhattan.

00:07:00.710 --> 00:07:06.447
And at the time she didn't
have any celebrity clients.

00:07:06.447 --> 00:07:08.530
She wanted to have them,
but she didn't have them.

00:07:08.530 --> 00:07:11.230
She read that Madonna was
looking for apartments.

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:15.400
So she called all the
news stations and said,

00:07:15.400 --> 00:07:18.890
I have a point of view on
what apartments Madonna should

00:07:18.890 --> 00:07:22.880
be looking at, and so she
got on the evening news,

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:27.200
and she was introduced as
the broker to the stars.

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:29.560
As I said, she didn't have
any celebrity clients.

00:07:29.560 --> 00:07:32.250
But as a result
of that interview,

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:37.990
she got a call the next day from
Richard Gere's agent saying,

00:07:37.990 --> 00:07:41.560
Richard Gere wants to find
an apartment in Manhattan.

00:07:41.560 --> 00:07:43.280
Do you think you
can meet with him?

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:44.280
She said, you know what?

00:07:44.280 --> 00:07:47.730
I think I can fit
it in, which leads

00:07:47.730 --> 00:07:51.360
to my third rule of branding.

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:53.120
It's all about perceptions.

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:55.440
Branding is all
about perceptions.

00:07:55.440 --> 00:07:58.720
It doesn't matter who's better.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:01.340
It's really what
perceptions are.

00:08:01.340 --> 00:08:05.140
When I was a kid and people
would make fun of me,

00:08:05.140 --> 00:08:06.780
I'd go crying to my mother.

00:08:06.780 --> 00:08:09.230
And she'd say, forget
about what other people say

00:08:09.230 --> 00:08:11.410
and what other people think.

00:08:11.410 --> 00:08:13.880
What's important
is what you think.

00:08:13.880 --> 00:08:15.850
But it's not true.

00:08:15.850 --> 00:08:18.100
It is important what
other people think.

00:08:18.100 --> 00:08:19.690
That was bad advice.

00:08:19.690 --> 00:08:21.600
And branding and
virtual branding

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:25.250
is about building positive
perceptions for brand you.

00:08:25.250 --> 00:08:27.420
And really branding
is about what

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:32.039
you do to the minds of other
people by what you're saying.

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:35.390
And that leads to my fourth
principle of branding.

00:08:35.390 --> 00:08:38.260
You always want to be
expanding into new markets.

00:08:38.260 --> 00:08:41.100
How has the market changed?

00:08:41.100 --> 00:08:44.850
One thing that's going on in
the whole technology area,

00:08:44.850 --> 00:08:48.760
according to Gartner 80%
of marketing tech decisions

00:08:48.760 --> 00:08:52.280
will be made by lines
of business by 2016.

00:08:52.280 --> 00:08:55.240
So there's a lot of
technology buyers

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:57.980
that aren't just
traditional IT guys that

00:08:57.980 --> 00:08:59.620
are going to be part of it.

00:08:59.620 --> 00:09:03.530
So thinking of new markets and
how to present yourself well

00:09:03.530 --> 00:09:05.040
in those new markets.

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:06.890
So then flash forward.

00:09:06.890 --> 00:09:10.462
Barbara sells her
business for $70 million.

00:09:10.462 --> 00:09:12.350
You see on "The Shark Tank" now.

00:09:12.350 --> 00:09:16.110
She's sort of brought her
brand into modern world.

00:09:16.110 --> 00:09:19.820
She's very active on
LinkedIn and television,

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:22.230
other social media.

00:09:22.230 --> 00:09:26.960
And it was interesting, because
she wrote a blog a couple weeks

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:31.870
ago that she did a mailing
to her clients and prospects.

00:09:31.870 --> 00:09:36.640
And she said I got more calls
about this marketing campaign

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:38.350
than anything else I did.

00:09:38.350 --> 00:09:42.260
And what was interesting
wasn't what was in the package.

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:44.330
It was the stamp that I used.

00:09:47.710 --> 00:09:49.310
She was pretty well-known.

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:51.490
It's not something we
can do and get away with,

00:09:51.490 --> 00:09:56.570
but she did a stamp with her
picture on it from [INAUDIBLE],

00:09:56.570 --> 00:09:59.090
and it got everybody
talking, which

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:01.880
leads to my next
principle of branding.

00:10:01.880 --> 00:10:03.900
You want to think outside in.

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:05.870
You want to think
of what reaction

00:10:05.870 --> 00:10:08.940
do I want to get
from buyers, and what

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:12.630
do I have to do to
get that reaction.

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:15.020
So if you want to get
in "The New York Times,

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:17.325
you need to provide information.

00:10:17.325 --> 00:10:19.040
Or if you want to be
quoted by the media,

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:22.030
you want to be providing
fresh information that no one

00:10:22.030 --> 00:10:23.970
else has provided them with.

00:10:23.970 --> 00:10:26.780
If you want to get
endorsed by Donald Trump

00:10:26.780 --> 00:10:28.870
and you don't know
him, you need to think

00:10:28.870 --> 00:10:31.030
of what is his mindset?

00:10:31.030 --> 00:10:33.365
How can I get him
to take the call?

00:10:33.365 --> 00:10:36.240
So you want to think
of who is my market,

00:10:36.240 --> 00:10:39.650
and what do I have to
do to reach that market?

00:10:39.650 --> 00:10:42.540
And my sixth
principle of branding

00:10:42.540 --> 00:10:45.580
is you want to
disguise your message.

00:10:45.580 --> 00:10:50.210
The branding world is all about
commercials that they really

00:10:50.210 --> 00:10:53.310
go into a really detailed
explanation of what

00:10:53.310 --> 00:10:55.750
the product is or
what the service is.

00:10:55.750 --> 00:10:58.910
It's really all about
image, how the brand

00:10:58.910 --> 00:11:03.020
makes you feel, the kind of
people that use that product.

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:06.520
So it's much more effective
to sell your story,

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:08.740
to wrap your brand
in a story, so

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:11.520
to tell stories and
do interesting things

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:14.760
that clients and prospects
are interested in.

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:16.270
And so here's Barbara today.

00:11:16.270 --> 00:11:18.950
This is her LinkedIn profile.

00:11:18.950 --> 00:11:23.670
She's an Influencer on LinkedIn,
so she's one of the bloggers

00:11:23.670 --> 00:11:27.290
that they feature
along with Jack

00:11:27.290 --> 00:11:32.020
Welch and other well-known
people, which leads me

00:11:32.020 --> 00:11:34.450
to my seventh rule of branding.

00:11:34.450 --> 00:11:39.000
You want to use LinkedIn to
build brand and increase sales.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.770
Here's an interesting statistic.

00:11:41.770 --> 00:11:47.600
64% of all corporate website
traffic comes from LinkedIn.

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:51.170
So it's a very powerful
area to build your brand,

00:11:51.170 --> 00:11:54.390
because so many people look
at things there and then go

00:11:54.390 --> 00:11:56.460
to visit a corporate website.

00:11:56.460 --> 00:11:58.050
Facebook is decreasing.

00:11:58.050 --> 00:11:59.450
It was 30%.

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:01.390
Now it's about 17%.

00:12:01.390 --> 00:12:03.850
And Twitter is in
the teens as well.

00:12:03.850 --> 00:12:07.940
But it's really
dominated by LinkedIn.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:11.230
It's got 180 million
members, but it's

00:12:11.230 --> 00:12:16.660
a very, very powerful
force for buyers.

00:12:16.660 --> 00:12:22.400
So all of the changes that have
happened in the sales world

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:24.410
and in the marketing
world have come

00:12:24.410 --> 00:12:27.210
about because of
the internet and how

00:12:27.210 --> 00:12:28.830
it's transformed everything.

00:12:28.830 --> 00:12:31.900
And we're all familiar with the
marketing funnel, the old way

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:36.070
of marketing and selling where
at the top it was a funnel.

00:12:36.070 --> 00:12:37.920
There were a lot of products.

00:12:37.920 --> 00:12:39.840
That's when
advertising took place.

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:41.490
And then it narrowed
down as people

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:43.250
went through the sales process.

00:12:43.250 --> 00:12:46.260
And then there was a lot of
activity at the other end,

00:12:46.260 --> 00:12:49.460
whether it was point of
purchase or one-to-one sales.

00:12:49.460 --> 00:12:53.900
Today the image is a
double-ended focus funnel,

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:57.240
because clients and
prospects have access

00:12:57.240 --> 00:12:58.790
to so much information.

00:12:58.790 --> 00:13:00.820
They educate themselves a lot.

00:13:00.820 --> 00:13:03.720
So it's push-pull marketing
that's taking place.

00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:07.350
It's not just people
pushing their message out

00:13:07.350 --> 00:13:10.830
but also clients
pulling the message in.

00:13:10.830 --> 00:13:16.730
One of the research studies show
that 57% of the sales decisions

00:13:16.730 --> 00:13:19.720
are made by clients,
are made by prospects

00:13:19.720 --> 00:13:25.180
before they even call somebody
to find out more information.

00:13:25.180 --> 00:13:28.460
So what's the mindset
of top social sellers?

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:30.910
There's been some studies done.

00:13:30.910 --> 00:13:34.790
Almost 90% of them use
LinkedIn as the focus,

00:13:34.790 --> 00:13:38.750
because that's where the fish
are that they want to get.

00:13:38.750 --> 00:13:41.710
They put a lot of attention
into doing their profile.

00:13:41.710 --> 00:13:45.150
Over 40% rate their
profile as well done.

00:13:45.150 --> 00:13:49.380
So they take the time to
write a very good summary.

00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:52.930
They focus a lot on the
headline, the visual, their job

00:13:52.930 --> 00:13:53.450
experience.

00:13:53.450 --> 00:13:55.270
Instead of just a
couple of sentences,

00:13:55.270 --> 00:13:56.650
they really tell a story.

00:13:56.650 --> 00:14:03.430
They talk in terms of framing
it almost like a business

00:14:03.430 --> 00:14:05.560
presentation-- here
was the challenge.

00:14:05.560 --> 00:14:07.240
Here's what was accomplished.

00:14:07.240 --> 00:14:12.540
Here were the obstacles--
when they do it.

00:14:12.540 --> 00:14:15.930
About 70% of them say they
spend six hours a week,

00:14:15.930 --> 00:14:17.830
roughly an hour a
day, on LinkedIn.

00:14:17.830 --> 00:14:21.290
So they really spend
time using LinkedIn.

00:14:21.290 --> 00:14:23.950
They use more
capabilities of LinkedIn

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:27.710
than other sellers,
