00:22:01.833 --> 00:22:02.708
CATHERINE KAPUTA: OK.

00:22:02.708 --> 00:22:03.645
OK, great.

00:22:03.645 --> 00:22:05.270
All right.

00:22:05.270 --> 00:22:08.810
So in the branding world, the
first thing you want to do

00:22:08.810 --> 00:22:10.720
is you're looking
for your brand idea.

00:22:10.720 --> 00:22:13.320
You're analyzing to find
your USP, your Unique Selling

00:22:13.320 --> 00:22:14.350
Proposition.

00:22:14.350 --> 00:22:17.670
There are some strategies
that a lot of brands use.

00:22:17.670 --> 00:22:20.830
So I'm going to just focus on
a couple of those strategies.

00:22:20.830 --> 00:22:23.036
And in the branding world,
when you have a product

00:22:23.036 --> 00:22:24.660
you explore different
ones, because you

00:22:24.660 --> 00:22:26.076
don't know which
is going to work.

00:22:26.076 --> 00:22:30.080
For example, when Volvo was
introduced in the United States

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:32.700
they were exploring a number
of different strategies.

00:22:32.700 --> 00:22:37.030
One was this attribute
strategy around safety.

00:22:37.030 --> 00:22:39.910
They were also exploring
an attribute strategy

00:22:39.910 --> 00:22:41.650
around durability.

00:22:41.650 --> 00:22:43.890
One of the other strategies
they were exploring

00:22:43.890 --> 00:22:51.275
was a heritage strategy, made
in Sweden, Swedish engineering.

00:22:51.275 --> 00:22:53.270
That didn't test too
well because Americans

00:22:53.270 --> 00:22:56.180
go, Swedish engineering, duh.

00:22:56.180 --> 00:22:58.610
But anyway, safety won out,
but it was an argument.

00:22:58.610 --> 00:23:04.780
So let's explore a couple of
common positioning strategies

00:23:04.780 --> 00:23:09.200
for brands that people can use
as well, and one is the expert.

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:13.670
Being an expert in a certain
area of business and standing

00:23:13.670 --> 00:23:16.980
for that with clients can be a
very, very powerful strategy.

00:23:16.980 --> 00:23:18.700
Here's Warren Buffett.

00:23:18.700 --> 00:23:20.430
What's he an expert in?

00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:21.910
Finance and investments.

00:23:21.910 --> 00:23:23.670
And so he owns that position.

00:23:23.670 --> 00:23:24.550
You really trust him.

00:23:24.550 --> 00:23:26.860
They call him the
Oracle of Omaha.

00:23:26.860 --> 00:23:30.390
And a tactic of an expert, if
you're positioning yourself

00:23:30.390 --> 00:23:34.250
as an expert, is
white papers, writing

00:23:34.250 --> 00:23:39.310
articles, trend reports, having
a point of view on the market

00:23:39.310 --> 00:23:40.360
because you're an expert.

00:23:40.360 --> 00:23:43.310
That was Barbara
Corcoran's strategy,

00:23:43.310 --> 00:23:46.840
thought leader in your niche.

00:23:46.840 --> 00:23:50.170
Industry events you're an
expert at as a panelist

00:23:50.170 --> 00:23:51.950
or as a speaker.

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:54.780
So it can be a very
powerful positioning

00:23:54.780 --> 00:23:56.560
strategy for brands.

00:23:56.560 --> 00:24:00.730
Another positioning strategy
is attribute positioning,

00:24:00.730 --> 00:24:05.360
and this is the most popular
positioning strategy of brands.

00:24:05.360 --> 00:24:07.720
It's looking at the category.

00:24:07.720 --> 00:24:13.440
What attributes are
important in that category?

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:16.260
Which attributes aren't
owned that I could own?

00:24:19.515 --> 00:24:21.310
I talked before about Volvo.

00:24:21.310 --> 00:24:24.120
They did an attribute
strategy around safety.

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:26.530
They made the car
more safe because they

00:24:26.530 --> 00:24:28.410
were doing that strategy.

00:24:28.410 --> 00:24:31.500
So it wasn't like
the chicken and egg.

00:24:31.500 --> 00:24:32.370
This was an idea.

00:24:32.370 --> 00:24:33.970
No one owned safety.

00:24:33.970 --> 00:24:37.340
It was important group
of people in the market

00:24:37.340 --> 00:24:39.950
that it was very powerful to.

00:24:39.950 --> 00:24:42.780
So looking at the car
category, who owns ruggedness?

00:24:42.780 --> 00:24:45.130
Who would you say,
in terms of cars?

00:24:45.130 --> 00:24:46.580
That's another attribute.

00:24:46.580 --> 00:24:47.500
AUDIENCE: Jeep.

00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:49.100
CATHERINE KAPUTA: OK, Jeep.

00:24:49.100 --> 00:24:51.380
If you look at
prestige, who owns that?

00:24:51.380 --> 00:24:52.874
That's another attribute.

00:24:52.874 --> 00:24:53.790
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:24:53.790 --> 00:24:55.230
CATHERINE KAPUTA: OK, Mercedes.

00:24:55.230 --> 00:24:57.830
So in the car category,
you see that a lot,

00:24:57.830 --> 00:25:00.570
looking at an attribute,
looking at an adjective that's

00:25:00.570 --> 00:25:03.860
available, and owning
that attribute.

00:25:03.860 --> 00:25:07.010
And that can be very
powerful for people,

00:25:07.010 --> 00:25:09.200
owning a particular attribute.

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:12.630
If you're in sales, it
could be a trusted adviser.

00:25:12.630 --> 00:25:14.360
You want to own an
attribute that's

00:25:14.360 --> 00:25:15.930
important to your
audience, so it's

00:25:15.930 --> 00:25:19.510
a different positioning
than expert.

00:25:19.510 --> 00:25:21.410
And the tactics here
are a little different,

00:25:21.410 --> 00:25:25.490
because you really in
attribute positioning

00:25:25.490 --> 00:25:29.820
go after endorsements,
recommendations.

00:25:29.820 --> 00:25:33.270
If your attribute is customer
service or client attention,

00:25:33.270 --> 00:25:35.930
you want to have a lot
of clients recommending

00:25:35.930 --> 00:25:39.620
you and mentioning your
attribute so that people really

00:25:39.620 --> 00:25:40.120
get that.

00:25:40.120 --> 00:25:43.820
And that's a part of your
summary in your profile

00:25:43.820 --> 00:25:45.690
is telling that story.

00:25:45.690 --> 00:25:48.790
You want to have success
stories with your client that

00:25:48.790 --> 00:25:50.770
demonstrates your attribute.

00:25:50.770 --> 00:25:53.070
You want your articles
that you write

00:25:53.070 --> 00:25:55.300
to reinforce that attribute.

00:25:55.300 --> 00:25:58.560
So you do everything the
ties that altogether.

00:25:58.560 --> 00:26:01.160
Another common
positioning strategy

