seconds or less people

00:37:48.580 --> 00:37:50.870
take you in, whether
they meet you in person

00:37:50.870 --> 00:37:53.100
or look at your
LinkedIn profile.

00:37:53.100 --> 00:37:56.030
Two seconds or
less, they take you,

00:37:56.030 --> 00:37:57.790
and they figure out
what you're all about.

00:38:00.869 --> 00:38:02.910
Malcolm Gladwell wrote a
book, "Blink," about it.

00:38:02.910 --> 00:38:04.784
In the blink of an eye,
we take something in.

00:38:04.784 --> 00:38:07.570
The interesting thing
about visual identity

00:38:07.570 --> 00:38:12.180
is what social scientists
call thin slicing.

00:38:12.180 --> 00:38:15.930
They're remarkably accurate,
and they're very sticky.

00:38:15.930 --> 00:38:17.410
They stick with us.

00:38:17.410 --> 00:38:20.060
So that's why you want to
think about first impressions

00:38:20.060 --> 00:38:23.600
and the impression that your
virtual brand gives as well.

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:25.930
They did studies at a
number of universities

00:38:25.930 --> 00:38:29.980
showing students a two-second
video of a professor

00:38:29.980 --> 00:38:32.800
before they took a
course with him or her,

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:35.610
and then they gave them the same
questionnaire five months later

00:38:35.610 --> 00:38:37.150
after they took a course.

00:38:37.150 --> 00:38:39.620
And they found that
that two-second slice

00:38:39.620 --> 00:38:42.070
that they saw of the
professor and what

00:38:42.070 --> 00:38:46.910
they wrote in their evaluation
was almost identical with what

00:38:46.910 --> 00:38:50.340
they wrote after being in that
person's class for five months.

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:53.940
So these snap impressions
are very powerful.

00:38:53.940 --> 00:38:55.970
They're very
powerful for people.

00:38:55.970 --> 00:38:58.360
The other thing that's
important about visual identity

00:38:58.360 --> 00:39:01.400
is there's a beauty premium.

00:39:01.400 --> 00:39:03.750
And the branding world
knows about that.

00:39:03.750 --> 00:39:06.000
That's why we spend a lot
of time in the way something

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:07.640
is packaged.

00:39:07.640 --> 00:39:10.990
Something that's well packaged,
you can charge more for it.

00:39:10.990 --> 00:39:12.930
People in tests,
they think there's

00:39:12.930 --> 00:39:17.180
more volume in it just
because of its packaging.

00:39:17.180 --> 00:39:19.020
It may or may not be true.

00:39:19.020 --> 00:39:20.700
And the same is
true with people.

00:39:20.700 --> 00:39:23.180
There was a study done
called "The Beauty Premium"

00:39:23.180 --> 00:39:26.570
by two professors, one
a Harvard economist

00:39:26.570 --> 00:39:29.130
and one a Wesleyan economist.

00:39:29.130 --> 00:39:30.640
They named it "The
Beauty Premium,"

00:39:30.640 --> 00:39:36.640
and they did a big study looking
at people and people that

00:39:36.640 --> 00:39:38.890
packaged themselves well.

00:39:38.890 --> 00:39:40.590
And we can all package
ourselves well,

00:39:40.590 --> 00:39:46.190
because interesting
looking is very attractive.

00:39:46.190 --> 00:39:48.660
The people that
packaged themselves well

00:39:48.660 --> 00:39:53.820
were hired over people that were
less attractive or packaged.

00:39:53.820 --> 00:39:56.230
And it had a halo effect.

00:39:56.230 --> 00:39:58.810
Because someone
looked good, people

00:39:58.810 --> 00:40:02.560
thought they were smarter than
people who didn't look as good.

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:07.510
And it had a whole halo effect
on a whole range of values,

00:40:07.510 --> 00:40:10.620
including being kinder and
more productive and worth more,

00:40:10.620 --> 00:40:12.020
et cetera, et cetera.

00:40:12.020 --> 00:40:14.070
So you want to think of
how you package yourself

00:40:14.070 --> 00:40:16.470
and here virtually on LinkedIn.

00:40:16.470 --> 00:40:20.180
I know you've all gotten your
pictures taken at Google,

00:40:20.180 --> 00:40:24.080
but you want to think of
the whole look of that.

00:40:24.080 --> 00:40:26.940
And the picture's important
because LinkedIn's research

00:40:26.940 --> 00:40:30.720
shows that your profile is 11
times more likely to be read

00:40:30.720 --> 00:40:34.100
and looked at if
you have a picture.

00:40:34.100 --> 00:40:36.930
The other thing we talk
about in the branding world

00:40:36.930 --> 00:40:39.820
is having a visual
hook for your brand.

00:40:39.820 --> 00:40:42.670
Twitter has its bird.

00:40:42.670 --> 00:40:45.550
Every brand tries to
have a visual hook

00:40:45.550 --> 00:40:49.610
so that it hooks in the
brand in the minds of people.

00:40:49.610 --> 00:40:53.880
And on LinkedIn, you can use
rich media in your summary.

00:40:53.880 --> 00:40:57.212
You can use it in your
Experience section

00:40:57.212 --> 00:41:00.690
and in your Education section.

00:41:00.690 --> 00:41:04.500
Here's an example from
a colleague that I know.

00:41:04.500 --> 00:41:07.270
She has an ebook, and there's
a picture of the ebook.

00:41:07.270 --> 00:41:09.900
She's got a little mini
slide presentation.

00:41:09.900 --> 00:41:13.350
You're not going to put your
slide presentation that you

00:41:13.350 --> 00:41:16.120
would give to a
client, but you could

00:41:16.120 --> 00:41:18.640
do five slides that are trends.

00:41:18.640 --> 00:41:20.830
Because a lot of people
are visually-oriented.

00:41:20.830 --> 00:41:25.180
So you could do things like that
that give your profile a very

00:41:25.180 --> 00:41:28.800
rich, robust look
rather than just text.

00:41:28.800 --> 00:41:32.260
You could have a speaking video
or if you were at a conference,

00:41:32.260 --> 00:41:36.240
a short clip that
people can see.

00:41:36.240 --> 00:41:38.594
Trend reports, other
things like that, you

00:41:38.594 --> 00:41:40.510
can have right there on
your LinkedIn profile,

00:41:40.510 --> 00:41:42.390
put a nice cover on it.

00:41:42.390 --> 00:41:48.720
So it gives your profile a
strong visual hook as well.

00:41:48.720 --> 00:41:51.490
So in terms of branding, when
we're packaging the brand

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:54.220
there's the visual identity,
which is very powerful,

00:41:54.220 --> 00:41:56.090
also the verbal identity.

00:41:56.090 --> 00:42:00.800
And the first critical
verbal identity decision

00:42:00.800 --> 00:42:02.610
we make in branding is the name.

00:42:02.610 --> 00:42:03.870
What are we going to name it?

00:42:03.870 --> 00:42:06.930
Google has a great name.

00:42:06.930 --> 00:42:08.630
It has meaning to it.

00:42:08.630 --> 00:42:12.130
It's an unusual name,
the double O, the two Gs.

00:42:12.130 --> 00:42:15.180
A lot of people copied
the double O thing

00:42:15.180 --> 00:42:17.010
with Google's success.

00:42:17.010 --> 00:42:19.972
But names are important
for people too.

00:42:19.972 --> 00:42:22.940
In Hollywood, for years
they changed their names

00:42:22.940 --> 00:42:26.300
to make a more attractive name.

00:42:26.300 --> 00:42:29.840
I sometimes ask people,
would Marilyn Monroe

00:42:29.840 --> 00:42:34.820
be the icon she it is today,
the beauty icon she is today

00:42:34.820 --> 00:42:36.950
if she had kept
her original name?

00:42:36.950 --> 00:42:38.664
Does anyone remember
her original name?

00:42:38.664 --> 00:42:39.580
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:39.580 --> 00:42:40.788
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Norma Jean.

00:42:40.788 --> 00:42:43.110
Is Norma a pretty name?

00:42:43.110 --> 00:42:44.454
What do you think?

00:42:44.454 --> 00:42:45.260
AUDIENCE: It's my
daughter's name.

00:42:45.260 --> 00:42:46.700
CATHERINE KAPUTA: It's
your daughter's name.

00:42:46.700 --> 00:42:47.570
It's a pretty name.

00:42:50.350 --> 00:42:54.830
Well, there was a study
done of two women that

00:42:54.830 --> 00:42:57.940
were viewed as
equally attractive,

00:42:57.940 --> 00:43:00.420
and then there was
the same picture

00:43:00.420 --> 00:43:04.140
shown to another group
asking about attractiveness.

00:43:04.140 --> 00:43:07.660
The only change that was
made was half the pictures

00:43:07.660 --> 00:43:12.690
had Elizabeth on them, and
then half had Gertrude.

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:15.310
Guess who wasn't
attractive anymore?

00:43:15.310 --> 00:43:15.820
Yeah.

00:43:15.820 --> 00:43:18.300
So names can hurt you.

00:43:18.300 --> 00:43:21.430
The other name you want to
think about from a branding

00:43:21.430 --> 00:43:23.980
perspective is how do
you label yourself?

00:43:23.980 --> 00:43:25.120
What do you call yourself?

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:27.670
That can help you
or hurt you too.

00:43:27.670 --> 00:43:29.970
And we don't take our own name.

00:43:29.970 --> 00:43:32.250
We don't give ourselves
our own names.

00:43:32.250 --> 00:43:35.610
But the fact of the
matter is unusual

00:43:35.610 --> 00:43:37.930
names are a real
benefit on the internet

00:43:37.930 --> 00:43:39.730
because you can own
your name, and you

00:43:39.730 --> 00:43:42.272
want to try to own
your name, dot com.

00:43:42.272 --> 00:43:43.010
Own your name.

00:43:43.010 --> 00:43:45.570
LinkedIn slash your name.

00:43:45.570 --> 00:43:47.690
It's easy to change that.

00:43:47.690 --> 00:43:50.850
But another important name
is how do you label yourself?

00:43:50.850 --> 00:43:53.390
How do you describe
what your job is?

00:43:53.390 --> 00:43:55.990
And that can help you or
hurt you was well too.

00:43:55.990 --> 00:44:00.080
There was a study done
showing people clips

00:44:00.080 --> 00:44:04.850
of a video of a
professor, same clip.

00:44:04.850 --> 00:44:07.890
Half of them labeled it
as humanistic psychology

00:44:07.890 --> 00:44:09.140
professor.

00:44:09.140 --> 00:44:12.920
And then the other group
saw the same video clip

00:44:12.920 --> 00:44:16.950
with the label
statistics professor.

00:44:16.950 --> 00:44:19.037
What do you think they
said about the professor

00:44:19.037 --> 00:44:20.745
when the label was
humanistic psychology?

00:44:23.700 --> 00:44:25.850
More interesting,
thoughtful, he'd

00:44:25.850 --> 00:44:28.424
be fair in grading,
blah, blah, blah.

00:44:28.424 --> 00:44:30.590
What do you think they said
when he was a statistics

00:44:30.590 --> 00:44:31.860
professor, the very same clip?

00:44:31.860 --> 00:44:32.730
AUDIENCE: Boring.

00:44:32.730 --> 00:44:33.920
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Boring.

00:44:33.920 --> 00:44:35.640
And he'd be a tough grader.

00:44:35.640 --> 00:44:36.950
I don't like him.

00:44:36.950 --> 00:44:38.160
Very same thing.

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:40.380
So you want to think of
how do you label yourself.

00:44:40.380 --> 00:44:43.160
Some companies, it's hard to
tell what somebody does when

00:44:43.160 --> 00:44:46.180
you read their job
title, so you want

00:44:46.180 --> 00:44:50.110
to translate that in
your LinkedIn profile

00:44:50.110 --> 00:44:53.480
so the target audience,
the prospects you're trying

00:44:53.480 --> 00:44:58.280
to reach can understand
what it is you do.

00:44:58.280 --> 00:45:01.470
The other thing we think
about in the branding world

00:45:01.470 --> 00:45:05.290
as we talked about a visual
hook is having a verbal hook,

00:45:05.290 --> 00:45:07.710
owning a word.

00:45:07.710 --> 00:45:08.470
Volvo we know.

00:45:08.470 --> 00:45:09.620
Who owns Search?

00:45:12.600 --> 00:45:17.750
So we think of owning a word,
a phrase, a name, a story.

00:45:17.750 --> 00:45:18.760
What's her phrase?

00:45:18.760 --> 00:45:19.530
AUDIENCE: Lean in.

00:45:19.530 --> 00:45:20.613
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Lean in.

00:45:20.613 --> 00:45:24.640
She could have named her book
"The Woman's Guide to Success."

00:45:24.640 --> 00:45:26.940
but that wouldn't have been
as smart from a branding

00:45:26.940 --> 00:45:29.540
perspective, because
she gave it a name that

00:45:29.540 --> 00:45:33.950
could be a mantra, that could
be calling, a rallying cry,

00:45:33.950 --> 00:45:38.310
just like Google has
become a name for Search.

00:45:38.310 --> 00:45:39.480
Let's google somebody.

00:45:39.480 --> 00:45:42.280
So owning a word
is very powerful.

00:45:42.280 --> 00:45:46.030
And writing that
book with that name

00:45:46.030 --> 00:45:48.870
made her a mega
business celebrity.

00:45:48.870 --> 00:45:51.477
She may have been well-known
at Google when she worked here,

00:45:51.477 --> 00:45:53.810
and she may have been well-known
in certain communities,

00:45:53.810 --> 00:45:57.350
but now she's a global star.

00:45:57.350 --> 00:46:00.030
So it's very powerful.

00:46:00.030 --> 00:46:01.810
And you want to think
of what your word is

00:46:01.810 --> 00:46:04.806
and what your phrases are
and use them in your profile

00:46:04.806 --> 00:46:06.305
and in your
conversation, because it

00:46:06.305 --> 00:46:09.410
can be a very powerful
positioning idea.

00:46:09.410 --> 00:46:09.910
All right.

00:46:09.910 --> 00:46:13.170
So let's explore couple
of ways of approaching it.

00:46:13.170 --> 00:46:16.660
I know you've been
working on your profiles.

00:46:16.660 --> 00:46:19.140
I'm going to talk about
three ways of approaching

00:46:19.140 --> 00:46:23.890
the headline for your
LinkedIn profile.

00:46:23.890 --> 00:46:26.100
One way to go is a
keyword headline.

00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:28.650
Think of keywords
that people would

00:46:28.650 --> 00:46:31.820
use to find somebody like
yourself that you want

00:46:31.820 --> 00:46:35.890
to own in the minds of others,
so global executive, supply

00:46:35.890 --> 00:46:38.830
chain operations, Six
Sigma black belt-- it's

00:46:38.830 --> 00:46:42.030
a little in more
tangible experience--

00:46:42.030 --> 00:46:44.640
ROI, outperformance,
strategic leader.

00:46:44.640 --> 00:46:46.710
So these are all
keywords that somebody

00:46:46.710 --> 00:46:48.920
might look for in
finding this person

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:50.840
or finding somebody
like them so they

00:46:50.840 --> 00:46:54.260
would come up and
search on LinkedIn.

00:46:54.260 --> 00:46:58.650
Another way of going is a
power statement headline,

00:46:58.650 --> 00:47:02.680
helping companies translate
business goals and ideas

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:07.930
into operational reality
and positive ROI.

00:47:07.930 --> 00:47:10.960
This is the same person I was
doing the keyword headline

00:47:10.960 --> 00:47:15.300
for I wrote a power
statement headline for.

00:47:15.300 --> 00:47:17.470
And another way
to go is a hybrid.

00:47:17.470 --> 00:47:20.900
So maybe begin with
a power statement

00:47:20.900 --> 00:47:24.910
and then have your keywords
so that people can find you.

