00:55:44.090 --> 00:55:47.110
We've all heard of 6
degrees of separation.

00:55:47.110 --> 00:55:51.640
Well, on LinkedIn and
Facebook, it's 4.74 degrees.

00:55:51.640 --> 00:55:53.180
They did a major study globally.

00:55:55.740 --> 00:55:57.830
Facebook got a lot
of attention with it.

00:55:57.830 --> 00:56:00.300
Even reaching people
in remote Siberia,

00:56:00.300 --> 00:56:02.410
they got there in
less than five hops.

00:56:02.410 --> 00:56:06.590
So it's really a way
to connect easier

00:56:06.590 --> 00:56:10.250
with more people
using the internet

00:56:10.250 --> 00:56:13.030
and using LinkedIn
and social media.

00:56:13.030 --> 00:56:16.290
And the way I see it
in terms of a network,

00:56:16.290 --> 00:56:17.790
there are four key
networks that you

00:56:17.790 --> 00:56:19.790
want to think of developing.

00:56:19.790 --> 00:56:24.680
Your strategic network
includes mentors, sponsors,

00:56:24.680 --> 00:56:26.600
people that you know
that connect you

00:56:26.600 --> 00:56:29.110
with a lot of other people,
what Malcolm Gladwell

00:56:29.110 --> 00:56:30.330
calls connectors.

00:56:30.330 --> 00:56:33.400
And that group also is allies.

00:56:33.400 --> 00:56:37.020
Reid Hoffman, the CEO
of LinkedIn, in his book

00:56:37.020 --> 00:56:39.670
"The Startup of You"
talks about his network.

00:56:39.670 --> 00:56:43.030
And he's got this
band of brothers,

00:56:43.030 --> 00:56:46.700
allies, guys at
different companies,

00:56:46.700 --> 00:56:49.600
non-competitive that
are friends with him,

00:56:49.600 --> 00:56:53.860
and they all text each other
with ideas and text each other

00:56:53.860 --> 00:56:55.300
try this or try that.

00:56:55.300 --> 00:56:58.856
So they've got a group of
peers getting information

00:56:58.856 --> 00:57:01.230
that you can't really get from
a mentor or a sponsor, who

00:57:01.230 --> 00:57:03.320
are generally more
senior people.

00:57:03.320 --> 00:57:05.680
He's got this band of allies.

00:57:05.680 --> 00:57:07.790
And in this strategic
network, these

00:57:07.790 --> 00:57:10.640
are people that have
strong career impact

00:57:10.640 --> 00:57:12.810
and also have strong
relationship strength.

00:57:12.810 --> 00:57:14.650
So they're all
people on LinkedIn

00:57:14.650 --> 00:57:18.790
and that would be
first-degree connections.

00:57:18.790 --> 00:57:21.870
But another very important
network is this core network.

00:57:21.870 --> 00:57:25.050
Again, it has very
strong career impact.

00:57:25.050 --> 00:57:28.710
These are people that are your
colleagues at your company,

00:57:28.710 --> 00:57:32.710
at Google, but also people in
the industry, your clients,

00:57:32.710 --> 00:57:35.010
and prospects.

00:57:35.010 --> 00:57:37.182
And some of them will be
first-degree contacts.

00:57:37.182 --> 00:57:39.640
Some of them will be people
that are second-degree contacts

00:57:39.640 --> 00:57:41.570
that you don't know that well.

00:57:41.570 --> 00:57:44.390
And one of the goals that
you want to do on LinkedIn

00:57:44.390 --> 00:57:48.040
is move more people
from second-degree

00:57:48.040 --> 00:57:49.550
to first-degree contacts.

00:57:49.550 --> 00:57:51.800
Because when they're a
first-degree contact,

00:57:51.800 --> 00:57:54.380
you can have unlimited
messaging with them, et cetera,

00:57:54.380 --> 00:57:56.750
and you have access to
who their network is.

00:57:56.750 --> 00:57:59.400
So that's sort of
part of the strategy

00:57:59.400 --> 00:58:03.030
is moving more people into
first-degree contacts.

00:58:03.030 --> 00:58:05.880
Now another group that's
an important network

00:58:05.880 --> 00:58:08.180
is what I'm calling soft links.

00:58:08.180 --> 00:58:10.600
These are people that
you don't know well.

00:58:10.600 --> 00:58:12.590
But they can be
valuable just the same,

00:58:12.590 --> 00:58:15.810
because they're
often useful when

00:58:15.810 --> 00:58:18.869
you have a particular target
in mind or things like that.

00:58:18.869 --> 00:58:20.660
So they're people that
you don't know well.

00:58:20.660 --> 00:58:22.390
And then bottom
right, I'm calling it

00:58:22.390 --> 00:58:23.860
a grassroots network.

00:58:23.860 --> 00:58:26.190
These are people that are
close family and friends.

00:58:26.190 --> 00:58:30.390
Again, not high career impact,
but very strong support system

00:58:30.390 --> 00:58:32.680
just the same.

00:58:32.680 --> 00:58:33.435
Sure.

