this for a real tool versus
using it as a Facebook

01:13:41.690 --> 01:13:43.460
alternative, and then
it carries no value,

01:13:43.460 --> 01:13:44.880
and you devalue
everything you do

01:13:44.880 --> 01:13:46.110
because you're in it so much?

01:13:46.110 --> 01:13:47.940
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

01:13:47.940 --> 01:13:49.650
I think we all have
somebody like that.

01:13:49.650 --> 01:13:55.280
And I think that you've got to
think of branding and a brand.

01:13:55.280 --> 01:13:57.870
You want to build an
image for yourself,

01:13:57.870 --> 01:13:59.390
you want to build
a conversation,

01:13:59.390 --> 01:14:01.110
you want to build
engagement, but you

01:14:01.110 --> 01:14:02.390
don't want to be annoying.

01:14:02.390 --> 01:14:05.300
And if you're annoying, nobody
wants to do business with you.

01:14:05.300 --> 01:14:07.310
It's just like any brand.

01:14:07.310 --> 01:14:09.960
So I think there's a
fine balance there.

01:14:09.960 --> 01:14:11.259
Is there are a number?

01:14:11.259 --> 01:14:12.550
I think you have to sense that.

01:14:12.550 --> 01:14:15.580
But yeah, there's certain
people that I get updates

01:14:15.580 --> 01:14:17.627
from every day and that
endorse a million people

01:14:17.627 --> 01:14:18.960
and all this stuff goes through.

01:14:18.960 --> 01:14:21.430
You could block those
people, by the way.

01:14:21.430 --> 01:14:23.494
But it's annoying.

01:14:23.494 --> 01:14:24.910
And so you have
to think about it.

01:14:24.910 --> 01:14:26.850
Yes, LinkedIn can
work against you.

01:14:26.850 --> 01:14:30.040
But I think also there's a
danger not using LinkedIn

01:14:30.040 --> 01:14:31.720
because your clients
are using it,

01:14:31.720 --> 01:14:34.530
your prospects are using it, and
your competitors are using it.

01:14:34.530 --> 01:14:39.290
So you want to use it to build
a positive image for yourself

01:14:39.290 --> 01:14:41.997
and build positive
relationships and nurture them,

01:14:41.997 --> 01:14:43.330
but you don't want to be a pest.

01:14:43.330 --> 01:14:47.940
And some people, I wonder
where's the day job?

01:14:47.940 --> 01:14:49.510
Because it's so annoying.

01:14:49.510 --> 01:14:52.120
So it's a fine balance, and
you have to figure that out.

01:14:52.120 --> 01:14:55.000
What's a good amount
of communication?

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:57.050
And a lot of it is
based on this whole idea

01:14:57.050 --> 01:15:02.440
of who is your target audience
and what kind of relationship,

01:15:02.440 --> 01:15:05.260
what kind of communication
would be effective with them.

01:15:05.260 --> 01:15:07.212
And if you're bombarding
people, then you

01:15:07.212 --> 01:15:09.170
devalue the whole thing,
and you're a nuisance,

01:15:09.170 --> 01:15:11.720
and they don't want to
do business with you.

01:15:11.720 --> 01:15:12.220
All right.

01:15:12.220 --> 01:15:16.380
So what do top sellers
value in terms of LinkedIn?

01:15:16.380 --> 01:15:18.540
Researching people
and companies is

01:15:18.540 --> 01:15:22.500
by far the dominant one,
this whole idea of leveraging

01:15:22.500 --> 01:15:26.160
second-degree contacts
and who they know.

01:15:26.160 --> 01:15:30.870
There's more detailed ways
to connect on LinkedIn.

01:15:30.870 --> 01:15:34.730
You can leverage your
company's contacts.

01:15:34.730 --> 01:15:39.360
There's stories of articles
written about this that they

01:15:39.360 --> 01:15:44.230
found out through LinkedIn that
an admin person's uncle was

01:15:44.230 --> 01:15:46.480
a CIO at a company,
and they wouldn't

01:15:46.480 --> 01:15:48.320
have found that
connection otherwise.

01:15:48.320 --> 01:15:50.280
So there's a lot of
things that can help you

01:15:50.280 --> 01:15:52.250
with maintaining
relationships, and we'll

01:15:52.250 --> 01:15:54.760
get into more detail
in a little bit.

01:15:54.760 --> 01:15:56.770
Electronic word of mouth.

01:15:56.770 --> 01:16:00.060
Word of mouth is the most
important kind of advertising,

01:16:00.060 --> 01:16:02.200
getting other people
to advocate for you.

01:16:02.200 --> 01:16:05.190
And LinkedIn gives you
vehicles for doing that.

01:16:05.190 --> 01:16:09.950
The most-used features are
who has viewed my profile.

01:16:09.950 --> 01:16:14.000
71% of the top sellers, that's
their most used-feature.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:20.790
People you may know, groups,
direct messaging is also cited.

01:16:20.790 --> 01:16:22.780
Top sellers in terms
of LinkedIn groups

01:16:22.780 --> 01:16:27.690
tend to belong to 30 groups,
whereas 36% overall just belong

01:16:27.690 --> 01:16:29.540
to 9 or 9.

01:16:29.540 --> 01:16:32.110
A lot of them join
alumni groups, too,

01:16:32.110 --> 01:16:34.392
which I've found
to be very helpful.

01:16:34.392 --> 01:16:35.850
There's something
about people that

01:16:35.850 --> 01:16:39.974
went to the same school that
will help you in ways that I

01:16:39.974 --> 01:16:41.640
haven't seen with
other kinds of things.

01:16:41.640 --> 01:16:43.340
So that can be an
important one too.

01:16:43.340 --> 01:16:47.690
Target industries,
obviously, functions.

01:16:47.690 --> 01:16:49.450
They work the Members page.

01:16:49.450 --> 01:16:51.370
They start looking at
who the members are

01:16:51.370 --> 01:16:56.000
and how they can work that to
build relationships with them.

01:16:56.000 --> 01:16:57.750
They join groups strategically.

01:16:57.750 --> 01:17:00.590
They look at who their
hot prospects are,

01:17:00.590 --> 01:17:03.880
what groups are they
in, join those groups,

01:17:03.880 --> 01:17:06.310
and trying to be part
of the conversation

01:17:06.310 --> 01:17:08.190
and build a
relationship that way.

01:17:08.190 --> 01:17:12.906
And if that person posts
questions, responding to them

01:17:12.906 --> 01:17:15.280
and getting a sense of what
they're interested in through

01:17:15.280 --> 01:17:16.590
means as well.

01:17:16.590 --> 01:17:19.790
You can follow conversations
of interest on groups.

01:17:19.790 --> 01:17:22.630
You could set up
a follow for that.

01:17:22.630 --> 01:17:29.060
So here I'm isolating six
search secrets of super sellers,

01:17:29.060 --> 01:17:31.310
according to research
that's out there.

01:17:31.310 --> 01:17:34.050
One, they use the
Advanced Search feature

01:17:34.050 --> 01:17:37.370
to establish winning
search parameters.

01:17:37.370 --> 01:17:41.120
They save that search
and create alerts

01:17:41.120 --> 01:17:44.080
so that when anything
changes within that group

01:17:44.080 --> 01:17:47.280
that they've targeted they get
an automatic update about it.

01:17:47.280 --> 01:17:50.630
So it's an easy way to
see who's new to that that

01:17:50.630 --> 01:17:53.040
meets those parameters that
weren't on the list before,

01:17:53.040 --> 01:17:55.380
et cetera.

01:17:55.380 --> 01:17:57.865
Browse the network
of your network.

01:17:57.865 --> 01:18:02.130
You can do this with
first-degree contacts only.

01:18:02.130 --> 01:18:06.310
And they have a feature that you
can do this automatic introduce

01:18:06.310 --> 01:18:07.147
with LinkedIn.

01:18:07.147 --> 01:18:08.730
But I think what a
lot of people don't

01:18:08.730 --> 01:18:12.100
realize is when you use
that the recipient sees

01:18:12.100 --> 01:18:16.130
the email that you wrote to your
first-degree contact as well

01:18:16.130 --> 01:18:21.670
as the message that
you're writing to them.

01:18:21.670 --> 01:18:24.560
So I think it's smarter to
really pick up the phone,

01:18:24.560 --> 01:18:27.040
and if somebody's a
first-degree contact, send them

01:18:27.040 --> 01:18:30.010
an email directly
and say, I see you're

01:18:30.010 --> 01:18:32.770
a first-degree contact
with so-and-so.

01:18:32.770 --> 01:18:36.710
And make it a positive thing,
not I want to sell to them,

01:18:36.710 --> 01:18:41.280
but we've sold similar
product to another company

01:18:41.280 --> 01:18:44.100
that really I think they'd be
interested in learning more

01:18:44.100 --> 01:18:47.660
about, and do you
feel comfortable

01:18:47.660 --> 01:18:49.070
introducing me personally?

01:18:49.070 --> 01:18:51.820
It's much better if there's
a personal introduction

01:18:51.820 --> 01:18:58.550
through email rather than using,
I think, the LinkedIn device.

01:18:58.550 --> 01:19:00.720
Number three is you
want to check out

01:19:00.720 --> 01:19:04.740
viewers of this profile also
viewed and people similar to.

01:19:04.740 --> 01:19:07.610
Now this is something
that top super sellers do,

01:19:07.610 --> 01:19:09.660
and it could give you
ideas of other people

01:19:09.660 --> 01:19:12.010
that could be good
leads for you.

01:19:12.010 --> 01:19:14.430
Likewise, check out who's
viewed your profile.

01:19:17.320 --> 01:19:20.480
Super sellers also do
active company searches,

01:19:20.480 --> 01:19:23.610
advanced search by
name or by parameters.

01:19:23.610 --> 01:19:25.700
And when you do a
company search like that,

01:19:25.700 --> 01:19:28.500
it'll list the people
that you're first-degree

01:19:28.500 --> 01:19:31.510
connected with, the top five.

01:19:31.510 --> 01:19:35.080
You can follow a
company, and you

01:19:35.080 --> 01:19:38.290
can view people who viewed
this company also viewed.

01:19:38.290 --> 01:19:42.770
So it's an easy way to
keep track of all of that.

01:19:42.770 --> 01:19:46.480
Super sellers also use
Groups strategically.

01:19:46.480 --> 01:19:50.400
They join groups that
prospects have joined.

01:19:50.400 --> 01:19:54.660
They join groups of people that
have access to top prospects.

01:19:54.660 --> 01:19:58.540
So if you have a CIO
target or a C-level target,

01:19:58.540 --> 01:20:01.820
you can join groups
that suppliers

01:20:01.820 --> 01:20:06.360
belong to or media people
or customers of theirs

01:20:06.360 --> 01:20:10.490
to build relationships and
then move to the next level.

01:20:10.490 --> 01:20:12.880
You can check the
group's About section,

01:20:12.880 --> 01:20:15.420
and it'll tell you who
what kind of members

01:20:15.420 --> 01:20:18.840
are in the group, how
active the group is,

01:20:18.840 --> 01:20:22.160
the seniority of
them, the location.

01:20:22.160 --> 01:20:24.510
And then, as I said, there's
a group of super sellers--

01:20:24.510 --> 01:20:26.250
and we'll get into
more detail later--

01:20:26.250 --> 01:20:30.910
that formed their own group to
sort of develop their thought

01:20:30.910 --> 01:20:34.010
leadership and also
develop relationships.

01:20:34.010 --> 01:20:36.610
And a key thing that
super sellers do too

01:20:36.610 --> 01:20:38.450
is they're easy to reach.

01:20:38.450 --> 01:20:40.110
They're easy to find.

01:20:40.110 --> 01:20:43.900
They have a lot of
keywords in their profiles,

01:20:43.900 --> 01:20:45.720
so they're easy to find.

01:20:45.720 --> 01:20:48.100
Their title is something
that people can understand,

01:20:48.100 --> 01:20:51.205
or they changed their title so
people understand who they are

01:20:51.205 --> 01:20:53.990
and what their function is.

01:20:53.990 --> 01:20:56.940
You can easily put contact
information in your profile,

01:20:56.940 --> 01:20:57.440
if you want.

01:20:57.440 --> 01:21:00.560
You can put your direct
email address, if you want,

01:21:00.560 --> 01:21:03.500
so that you're easy to reach.

01:21:03.500 --> 01:21:06.470
So step one is you want
to build your brand.

01:21:06.470 --> 01:21:10.260
Step two is you want to find the
right customers for yourself.

01:21:10.260 --> 01:21:12.540
And step three is
about engagement.

01:21:12.540 --> 01:21:15.790
So how do you engage these
people and get a dialogue going

01:21:15.790 --> 01:21:18.089
and build a relationship?

01:21:18.089 --> 01:21:19.880
And the first thing
you want to think about

01:21:19.880 --> 01:21:21.710
is who is your target audience?

01:21:21.710 --> 01:21:27.820
So that point I was making
earlier, who is your audience?

01:21:27.820 --> 01:21:31.460
What reaction, what action
do I want them to take?

01:21:31.460 --> 01:21:34.910
And what do I have to
do to get that reaction?

01:21:34.910 --> 01:21:39.420
And having been a corporate
person in the marketing

01:21:39.420 --> 01:21:42.280
area, the CIO target,
in my opinion,

01:21:42.280 --> 01:21:44.100
is very different
from the CMO target,

01:21:44.100 --> 01:21:46.560
if you're branching out
into these other areas.

01:21:46.560 --> 01:21:50.660
And according to Gartner, 80%
of marketing tech spending

01:21:50.660 --> 01:21:53.630
will be in LBOs in
two years' time.

01:21:53.630 --> 01:21:56.000
So it's an audience
to think about.

01:21:56.000 --> 01:21:58.880
A lot of tech
companies are going

01:21:58.880 --> 01:22:01.620
after other areas
of the C-suite.

01:22:01.620 --> 01:22:06.840
And the CIO, in my experience
working on Wall Street,

01:22:06.840 --> 01:22:10.120
they were more risk-adverse
than marketing people,

01:22:10.120 --> 01:22:12.610
and they didn't want
to see a lot of change

01:22:12.610 --> 01:22:16.500
and upset the system, a
much more traditional kind

01:22:16.500 --> 01:22:18.990
of person, so a
different kind of sell

01:22:18.990 --> 01:22:22.900
than a CMO who is always charged
with what are you doing next,

01:22:22.900 --> 01:22:24.420
what kind of
exciting new things.

01:22:24.420 --> 01:22:27.820
Or the CEO was always
calling [INAUDIBLE], oh, I

01:22:27.820 --> 01:22:30.154
talked to this other
CEO at this company,

01:22:30.154 --> 01:22:31.320
and this is what he's doing.

01:22:31.320 --> 01:22:33.370
Have you thought of trying that?

01:22:33.370 --> 01:22:36.250
So it's always
what's new and what's

01:22:36.250 --> 01:22:41.400
innovative to bring in new
customers for the company.

01:22:41.400 --> 01:22:45.780
And now so much of the
marketing is technology-based

01:22:45.780 --> 01:22:48.225
because of the whole
importance of the internet

01:22:48.225 --> 01:22:53.380
and digital media and the whole
importance of social media.

01:22:53.380 --> 01:22:56.780
If I'm going to be judged on it,
I want to control the budget.

01:22:56.780 --> 01:22:59.960
So that's why so much is
moving into marketing and LBOs.

01:22:59.960 --> 01:23:03.030
Right now a lot of it
is smaller business,

01:23:03.030 --> 01:23:05.014
but I think it's
going to be growing.

01:23:05.014 --> 01:23:07.430
And a key thing you want to
think about in this whole area

01:23:07.430 --> 01:23:11.210
of how do you engage your
target audience is you

01:23:11.210 --> 01:23:13.300
always want to be
connecting with them,

01:23:13.300 --> 01:23:15.250
not annoying them, but
connecting with them

01:23:15.250 --> 01:23:16.310
in a meaningful way.

01:23:16.310 --> 01:23:18.530
But a big thing
in branding today

01:23:18.530 --> 01:23:21.900
is emotional branding,
understanding

01:23:21.900 --> 01:23:25.110
what your clients and
prospects are thinking about,

01:23:25.110 --> 01:23:28.360
what their problems are,
what their mindset is,

01:23:28.360 --> 01:23:32.250
and connecting with that
in an emotional way.

01:23:32.250 --> 01:23:35.410
Much more powerful
than rational arguments

01:23:35.410 --> 01:23:38.446
are connecting with
people emotionally.

01:23:38.446 --> 01:23:39.820
Just think when
you meet somebody

01:23:39.820 --> 01:23:41.920
that you have a mutual
friend in common.

01:23:41.920 --> 01:23:45.640
There's quick rapport that's
established because you

01:23:45.640 --> 01:23:50.220
both have this bond with
somebody you both know.

01:23:50.220 --> 01:23:52.200
I'm doing this
whole always series.

01:23:52.200 --> 01:23:54.420
So you always want
to be connecting.

01:23:54.420 --> 01:23:57.580
You always want to be
tracking competitors.

01:23:57.580 --> 01:24:00.780
This is a new thing that
LinkedIn introduced about two

01:24:00.780 --> 01:24:08.990
weeks ago, and it's a new tool,
tracking companies on LinkedIn

01:24:08.990 --> 01:24:11.390
and how important
different companies are.

01:24:11.390 --> 01:24:15.600
And here it shows you've got
some 500-pound gorillas here

01:24:15.600 --> 01:24:22.090
on LinkedIn, Microsoft,
IBM, Oracle, HP, Google.

01:24:22.090 --> 01:24:25.060
This was done by
looking at the target

01:24:25.060 --> 01:24:26.584
audience of these companies.

01:24:26.584 --> 01:24:28.250
And this is a high-tech
one, and they've

01:24:28.250 --> 01:24:29.790
done it for every industry.

01:24:29.790 --> 01:24:32.060
So you can see
the companies that

01:24:32.060 --> 01:24:35.720
are spending a lot on
content on LinkedIn,

01:24:35.720 --> 01:24:39.120
that have a lot of employees,
that are engaged on LinkedIn.

01:24:44.060 --> 01:24:47.180
They just posted this
a couple days ago.

01:24:47.180 --> 01:24:50.730
So what they're trying
to do, obviously,

01:24:50.730 --> 01:24:53.860
is to get the companies that
aren't as strong on LinkedIn

01:24:53.860 --> 01:24:59.470
to get a stronger position, get
more of their people involved

01:24:59.470 --> 01:25:02.750
with LinkedIn, to also get more
involved with corporate ads, et

01:25:02.750 --> 01:25:03.500
cetera, et cetera.

01:25:03.500 --> 01:25:07.350
So it measures all of that, all
of the people at a company--

01:25:07.350 --> 01:25:08.520
yes.

01:25:08.520 --> 01:25:09.680
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:25:09.680 --> 01:25:10.440
CATHERINE KAPUTA: No, no.

01:25:10.440 --> 01:25:11.210
That was my point.

01:25:11.210 --> 01:25:14.190
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:25:14.190 --> 01:25:16.260
We heard a rumor
a little while ago

01:25:16.260 --> 01:25:19.700
that if you link with
somebody-- for example,

01:25:19.700 --> 01:25:22.670
if I link with somebody
from Microsoft--

01:25:22.670 --> 01:25:26.250
can they then see everybody I'm
linking with from that point

01:25:26.250 --> 01:25:27.450
on?

01:25:27.450 --> 01:25:28.540
What do they see?

01:25:28.540 --> 01:25:29.520
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Yes.

01:25:29.520 --> 01:25:30.150
Yeah.

01:25:30.150 --> 01:25:32.000
Yeah, you're a
first-degree connection.

01:25:32.000 --> 01:25:33.360
Yes.

01:25:33.360 --> 01:25:34.147
Yes.

01:25:34.147 --> 01:25:35.980
AUDIENCE: So I heard
that they were actively

01:25:35.980 --> 01:25:37.802
doing that to see who
we're connecting with.

01:25:37.802 --> 01:25:38.606
AUDIENCE: Of course they are.

01:25:38.606 --> 01:25:39.310
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Yeah.

01:25:39.310 --> 01:25:40.400
AUDIENCE: So what
should we do about that?

01:25:40.400 --> 01:25:41.470
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Then
you can't connect--

01:25:41.470 --> 01:25:42.470
AUDIENCE: Don't connect
with anyone from Microsoft?

01:25:42.470 --> 01:25:43.428
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Yeah.

01:25:43.428 --> 01:25:44.710
But they will see that, yes.

01:25:44.710 --> 01:25:46.030
They will see that.

01:25:46.030 --> 01:25:48.030
And yes, you can
see LinkedIn has

01:25:48.030 --> 01:25:53.280
been a big strategy
of Microsoft and IBM

01:25:53.280 --> 01:25:54.475
and these other companies.

01:25:54.475 --> 01:25:55.391
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:25:57.372 --> 01:25:58.330
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Yeah.

01:25:58.330 --> 01:25:59.246
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:25:59.246 --> 01:26:00.544
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Yes.

01:26:00.544 --> 01:26:01.460
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:26:01.460 --> 01:26:02.020
CATHERINE KAPUTA:
Yeah, so you've

01:26:02.020 --> 01:26:04.500
got to think about who the
first-degree connections are

01:26:04.500 --> 01:26:05.522
going to be.

01:26:05.522 --> 01:26:07.980
You've got to think about who
your first-degree connections

01:26:07.980 --> 01:26:11.470
are going to be, because
they would have access

01:26:11.470 --> 01:26:14.190
to your network.

01:26:14.190 --> 01:26:14.840
