You always want to be
liking and commenting,

01:38:44.350 --> 01:38:47.490
particularly if clients or
prospects are posting something

01:38:47.490 --> 01:38:48.400
on the internet.

01:38:48.400 --> 01:38:50.160
And it's just like Facebook.

01:38:50.160 --> 01:38:52.630
It's very easy to do.

01:38:52.630 --> 01:38:54.510
But again, it's
touching someone.

01:38:54.510 --> 01:38:57.690
Also, I'm going to talk
later about touchpoints.

01:38:57.690 --> 01:38:59.350
But in the branding
world we think

01:38:59.350 --> 01:39:03.630
about touchpoints, every place
a brand and a person touch.

01:39:03.630 --> 01:39:06.840
And the whole game is to
increase the touchpoints,

01:39:06.840 --> 01:39:08.710
to also have them
all consistent.

01:39:08.710 --> 01:39:11.910
You don't want to have a bad
voicemail message that you

01:39:11.910 --> 01:39:15.350
sound harried and a very
professional website.

01:39:15.350 --> 01:39:19.050
You've got to have
it all work together.

01:39:19.050 --> 01:39:22.110
But all that's valuable.

01:39:22.110 --> 01:39:25.955
Always be connecting via Groups.

01:39:25.955 --> 01:39:28.330
One of the things that's good
about a lot of these groups

01:39:28.330 --> 01:39:29.520
is you can find the pain points.

01:39:29.520 --> 01:39:31.160
There's always people
asking questions.

01:39:31.160 --> 01:39:35.610
Does anyone have ideas on
how you solve this problem?

01:39:35.610 --> 01:39:39.380
So answer questions, ask
questions, answer questions.

01:39:39.380 --> 01:39:43.690
That can be a very good vehicle
for that kind of thing too.

01:39:43.690 --> 01:39:45.800
And as I said earlier,
be easy to reach.

01:39:45.800 --> 01:39:49.370
But Groups can be a
very interesting way

01:39:49.370 --> 01:39:52.060
to get to know people
that they could

01:39:52.060 --> 01:39:55.590
be potential clients and
prospects or allies of yours

01:39:55.590 --> 01:39:57.590
to help each other.

01:39:57.590 --> 01:39:58.940
Always be repurposing.

01:39:58.940 --> 01:40:02.660
I had this conversation
with somebody earlier.

01:40:02.660 --> 01:40:05.990
Everything that I
write a blog post on,

01:40:05.990 --> 01:40:12.230
I do several different tweets on
it with different facets of it.

01:40:12.230 --> 01:40:14.720
Somebody was saying if
I've posted an article,

01:40:14.720 --> 01:40:16.910
should I also blog about it?

01:40:16.910 --> 01:40:19.700
Yes, but write it a little
differently, a little different

01:40:19.700 --> 01:40:22.450
headline, change a
couple sentences around.

01:40:22.450 --> 01:40:24.820
Not everybody saw
the article, so you

01:40:24.820 --> 01:40:28.550
want to use all these
different channels.

01:40:28.550 --> 01:40:31.860
If you have a slide deck
that's resonating with clients,

01:40:31.860 --> 01:40:34.670
think is there a way to make
five slides out of it that

01:40:34.670 --> 01:40:36.570
would be OK in a public deck?

01:40:36.570 --> 01:40:38.590
Because your competitors
could see it as well.

01:40:38.590 --> 01:40:40.790
But you're looking
at your prospects.

01:40:40.790 --> 01:40:44.420
And a lot of people are
very visually-oriented,

01:40:44.420 --> 01:40:45.850
and there's a lot
of research that

01:40:45.850 --> 01:40:50.790
shows that when you tell
a story with visuals

01:40:50.790 --> 01:40:53.120
people remember it much
more than if they're just

01:40:53.120 --> 01:40:54.430
reading an article.

01:40:54.430 --> 01:40:57.290
So that's why a slide
thing with pictures

01:40:57.290 --> 01:41:02.200
and a couple of sentences
can be very, very effective.

01:41:02.200 --> 01:41:04.630
And I threw the top five
trends to transforming

01:41:04.630 --> 01:41:07.840
retail or an infographic.

01:41:07.840 --> 01:41:10.000
If you have a
complicated report,

01:41:10.000 --> 01:41:12.590
you could do an infographic
on it, things like that.

01:41:12.590 --> 01:41:14.060
You want to think creatively.

01:41:14.060 --> 01:41:16.760
But everything I'd
repurpose into at least

01:41:16.760 --> 01:41:20.530
four different ways or more.

01:41:20.530 --> 01:41:24.000
And you always want to
be linking and tracking.

01:41:24.000 --> 01:41:29.040
IBM got a lot of attention
with this social media campaign

01:41:29.040 --> 01:41:31.580
that they developed for
their web-based services

01:41:31.580 --> 01:41:33.272
which they weren't
selling that well.

01:41:33.272 --> 01:41:34.730
It wasn't going
that well for them.

01:41:34.730 --> 01:41:39.079
So they decided to do a social
media approach on LinkedIn.

01:41:39.079 --> 01:41:40.620
And I don't know
what their base was,

01:41:40.620 --> 01:41:43.260
but they claim in
the articles about it

01:41:43.260 --> 01:41:47.480
that they increased sales
400% with social selling link.

01:41:47.480 --> 01:41:49.880
And they linked it
to a landing page,

01:41:49.880 --> 01:41:53.010
so they were able
to track easily

01:41:53.010 --> 01:41:56.550
what resources people
were clicking on

01:41:56.550 --> 01:41:58.230
and what was working,
and then they

01:41:58.230 --> 01:42:00.802
made sure things
were followed up.

01:42:00.802 --> 01:42:05.850
And there's another
study by HubSpot looking

01:42:05.850 --> 01:42:09.870
at their clients and that
LinkedIn generated the highest

01:42:09.870 --> 01:42:13.940
visitor lead conversion
rate, 2.74%, which

01:42:13.940 --> 01:42:17.420
is a pretty good conversion
rate compared to Twitter

01:42:17.420 --> 01:42:19.970
and Facebook, which
were all under 1%.

01:42:19.970 --> 01:42:25.920
So this idea of using LinkedIn
and linking it to a landing

01:42:25.920 --> 01:42:29.765
page where you can track leads
and then follow up on them

01:42:29.765 --> 01:42:30.890
can be very, very valuable.

01:42:33.900 --> 01:42:37.070
So we talked about
step one is brand,

01:42:37.070 --> 01:42:39.530
step two is finding
the right people,

01:42:39.530 --> 01:42:44.890
step three is engaging
them, and step four

01:42:44.890 --> 01:42:46.640
is building relationships.

01:42:46.640 --> 01:42:50.320
You want to build
relationships with people.

01:42:50.320 --> 01:42:55.250
And a big thing in relationship
building in the branding world

01:42:55.250 --> 01:42:58.600
and branding effectiveness is
what we call brand likeability,

01:42:58.600 --> 01:43:01.050
building the
brand's personality.

01:43:01.050 --> 01:43:04.360
And whatever the product is, we
write a personality statement

01:43:04.360 --> 01:43:07.907
for the brand as if
it were a person,

01:43:07.907 --> 01:43:10.490
because it makes it easy for all
the different creative people

01:43:10.490 --> 01:43:12.090
that work on it.

01:43:12.090 --> 01:43:14.360
And I always say
brands are like people,

01:43:14.360 --> 01:43:15.810
and people are like brands.

01:43:15.810 --> 01:43:19.740
And they measure a brand's
likeability with a Q Score,

01:43:19.740 --> 01:43:23.750
and it measures both products,
in terms of likeability,

01:43:23.750 --> 01:43:24.920
and people.

01:43:24.920 --> 01:43:27.250
All the celebrities
have a Q Score.

01:43:27.250 --> 01:43:31.530
And the celebrities
with the highest Q Score

01:43:31.530 --> 01:43:33.670
make more money in
movie contracts.

01:43:33.670 --> 01:43:36.090
They get asked to
endorse things.

01:43:36.090 --> 01:43:39.350
And the likeability,
the Q Score can go down.

01:43:39.350 --> 01:43:44.440
I'm sure Oscar Pistorius'
Q Score is underwater now.

01:43:44.440 --> 01:43:49.590
And after the Olympics last
summer, he became very famous

01:43:49.590 --> 01:43:53.840
and had received a
number of endorsements.

01:43:53.840 --> 01:43:59.322
So I'm going to test your
ability to judge a Q Score.

01:43:59.322 --> 01:44:01.280
Let's look at a few famous
people, and tell me,

01:44:01.280 --> 01:44:03.013
who has the higher Q Score?

01:44:05.791 --> 01:44:06.708
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:44:06.708 --> 01:44:08.040
CATHERINE KAPUTA: You know what?

01:44:08.040 --> 01:44:09.180
The guys say Angelina.

01:44:09.180 --> 01:44:10.537
But who's got the higher--

01:44:10.537 --> 01:44:11.120
AUDIENCE: Jen,

01:44:11.120 --> 01:44:13.570
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Jen
has the higher Q Score.

01:44:13.570 --> 01:44:15.494
Why is she more likable?

01:44:15.494 --> 01:44:16.410
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:44:16.410 --> 01:44:16.630
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

01:44:16.630 --> 01:44:17.370
Less provocative.

01:44:17.370 --> 01:44:17.870
OK.

01:44:17.870 --> 01:44:21.590
So she's more like the
girl next door, right?

01:44:21.590 --> 01:44:22.420
What else about--

01:44:22.420 --> 01:44:23.806
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:44:23.806 --> 01:44:25.680
CATHERINE KAPUTA: She
wasn't the other woman.

01:44:25.680 --> 01:44:26.930
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:44:26.930 --> 01:44:30.420
CATHERINE KAPUTA: She's
a sympathetic character.

01:44:30.420 --> 01:44:31.840
She lost her guy.

01:44:31.840 --> 01:44:32.340
She is.

01:44:32.340 --> 01:44:33.200
But you know what?

01:44:33.200 --> 01:44:35.730
It's funny,
likeability, we're going

01:44:35.730 --> 01:44:37.590
to get into the factors
of that in a second.

01:44:37.590 --> 01:44:39.170
Anyway, let's look at two guys.

01:44:39.170 --> 01:44:40.800
Who's got the higher Q Score?

01:44:40.800 --> 01:44:41.792
AUDIENCE: Tom Hanks.

01:44:41.792 --> 01:44:42.290
AUDIENCE: Tom Hanks.

01:44:42.290 --> 01:44:44.476
CATHERINE KAPUTA: And why
is Tom Hanks more likable?

01:44:44.476 --> 01:44:45.392
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:44:48.150 --> 01:44:49.610
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Yeah.

01:44:49.610 --> 01:44:51.590
And likability's
important for people.

01:44:51.590 --> 01:44:53.920
That's a key thing
as a salesperson.

01:44:53.920 --> 01:44:57.640
Likeability and brand
personality are very key.

01:44:57.640 --> 01:44:59.580
And what are the
factors in likeability

01:44:59.580 --> 01:45:01.360
from a branding perspective?

01:45:01.360 --> 01:45:05.090
You want to be attractive
but not too attractive

01:45:05.090 --> 01:45:06.510
that people hate you.

01:45:11.216 --> 01:45:14.400
You want to be similar
so people feel, gee,

01:45:14.400 --> 01:45:16.580
I can relate to that person.

01:45:16.580 --> 01:45:19.400
That's somebody I can imagine
having a glass of wine with

01:45:19.400 --> 01:45:20.190
or a beer with.

01:45:20.190 --> 01:45:24.980
So the similarity principle
is very powerful for brands.

01:45:24.980 --> 01:45:28.340
The empathy principle, I
think the person feels and can

01:45:28.340 --> 01:45:31.520
feel my pain and I
can understand them.

01:45:31.520 --> 01:45:33.820
So the empathy
principle is important.

01:45:33.820 --> 01:45:36.060
And also the
familiarity principle,

01:45:36.060 --> 01:45:38.440
I'm aware who this person is.

01:45:38.440 --> 01:45:41.230
People like things that are
more familiar, it turns out.

01:45:41.230 --> 01:45:42.760
So that's one of
the reasons why you

01:45:42.760 --> 01:45:45.620
want to build your
profile as well.

01:45:45.620 --> 01:45:50.540
And Hanks seems very authentic.

01:45:50.540 --> 01:45:53.148
You like the guy.

01:45:53.148 --> 01:45:53.740
All right.

01:45:53.740 --> 01:45:59.300
So in building relationships,
you want to always be clicking.

01:45:59.300 --> 01:46:02.750
Social scientists call
sales people and others

01:46:02.750 --> 01:46:07.500
that establish rapport quickly
with somebody clickers.

01:46:07.500 --> 01:46:10.320
They have this ability
to find connection.

01:46:10.320 --> 01:46:14.160
And it the big secret
of clickers are they

01:46:14.160 --> 01:46:15.950
find similarity.

01:46:15.950 --> 01:46:19.110
They find mutual
interests or something

01:46:19.110 --> 01:46:22.114
in common with the other person.

01:46:22.114 --> 01:46:24.030
Super sellers-- there's
been a lot of research

01:46:24.030 --> 01:46:27.520
on this-- in a meeting
with prospects,

01:46:27.520 --> 01:46:30.640
they get on the same
wavelength as the prospect,

01:46:30.640 --> 01:46:33.235
and it's almost like
they're in sync.

01:46:36.640 --> 01:46:41.310
In some of the tests, they think
at the same breathing patterns.

01:46:41.310 --> 01:46:44.830
Whether it's consciously
or unconsciously,

01:46:44.830 --> 01:46:48.980
they mimic the gestures
even of the prospect,

01:46:48.980 --> 01:46:51.930
and they sort of get in
a mind meld with them.

01:46:51.930 --> 01:46:54.920
And LinkedIn provides
you with a lot

01:46:54.920 --> 01:46:58.050
of information about
clients and prospects

01:46:58.050 --> 01:47:00.720
to build on this whole
bond of similarity.

01:47:00.720 --> 01:47:03.680
Because similarity is
how people connect,

01:47:03.680 --> 01:47:07.370
and it really contributes to
this whole likeability factor

01:47:07.370 --> 01:47:10.090
that we were talking about.

01:47:10.090 --> 01:47:13.640
And LinkedIn also tells you a
lot of ways you're connected,

01:47:13.640 --> 01:47:16.950
similar skills that
you have with somebody,

01:47:16.950 --> 01:47:20.142
similar people that you
know in common, groups.

01:47:20.142 --> 01:47:22.100
And then they have this
on the right-hand panel

01:47:22.100 --> 01:47:23.270
when you get to anyone.

01:47:23.270 --> 01:47:27.050
So you could also mine
somebody's profile

01:47:27.050 --> 01:47:30.510
for detailed
information, but also

01:47:30.510 --> 01:47:33.560
they graphically show
you a lot of ideas.

01:47:33.560 --> 01:47:35.570
You always want to
be connecting dots.

01:47:35.570 --> 01:47:39.180
And I think that LinkedIn
provides a lot of information

01:47:39.180 --> 01:47:42.700
of how to connect the dots,
of how people are connected

01:47:42.700 --> 01:47:45.570
to other people, what
their interests are,

01:47:45.570 --> 01:47:48.460
what their groups are, a
lot of things like that that

01:47:48.460 --> 01:47:51.300
can be very useful in
terms of your pitch,

01:47:51.300 --> 01:47:54.340
whether it's in
person or online.

01:47:54.340 --> 01:47:56.900
This is a point that
Reid Hoffman made,

01:47:56.900 --> 01:48:02.100
the CEO of LinkedIn his
book, "The Startup of You"

01:48:02.100 --> 01:48:05.080
is this whole idea of giving
little gifts-- we're not

01:48:05.080 --> 01:48:08.490
talking "gifts" in quotes
here-- sending an article,

01:48:08.490 --> 01:48:11.810
offering advice,
making an introduction,

01:48:11.810 --> 01:48:15.940
writing a rec on LinkedIn,
offering to critique something.

01:48:15.940 --> 01:48:18.150
And there's a lot
of studies that

01:48:18.150 --> 01:48:22.780
show that if you do at
least two of these gifts

01:48:22.780 --> 01:48:25.920
before you make a sales pitch,
you'll be much more successful.

01:48:25.920 --> 01:48:29.610
One seller started
out with 300 leads,

01:48:29.610 --> 01:48:32.490
did this gifting
strategy, and then

01:48:32.490 --> 01:48:36.120
reached out to introduce
yourself and link

01:48:36.120 --> 01:48:38.640
and got a 65% return
rate, so now they're

01:48:38.640 --> 01:48:39.950
on a first-level basis.

01:48:39.950 --> 01:48:43.020
So it's an interesting
way to sort of build

01:48:43.020 --> 01:48:44.347
that initial relationship.

01:48:44.347 --> 01:48:45.680
I think we have a question here.

01:48:45.680 --> 01:48:45.900
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:48:45.900 --> 01:48:47.525
Just coming back to your
last slide for a minute,

01:48:47.525 --> 01:48:49.630
it just prompted me to
think about something,

01:48:49.630 --> 01:48:51.650
or another slide back.

01:48:54.350 --> 01:48:56.250
In the selling
world, a lot of us

01:48:56.250 --> 01:48:58.780
have accounts that are
direct competitors.

01:48:58.780 --> 01:49:00.050
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

01:49:00.050 --> 01:49:02.950
AUDIENCE: What's any advice
you have on that, as far as

01:49:02.950 --> 01:49:06.890
how you deal with-- It's
like dating multiple people.

01:49:06.890 --> 01:49:07.890
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

01:49:07.890 --> 01:49:09.265
AUDIENCE: It can
be a lot of work

01:49:09.265 --> 01:49:11.210
when you're trying to
put an article out there

01:49:11.210 --> 01:49:13.530
to get one person thinking.

01:49:13.530 --> 01:49:17.790
But it might be what their
direct competitor's doing.

01:49:17.790 --> 01:49:18.790
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

01:49:18.790 --> 01:49:21.155
Well, this is going to be
a problem in the business

01:49:21.155 --> 01:49:21.780
that you're in.

01:49:21.780 --> 01:49:23.440
And I think that
what you have to do

01:49:23.440 --> 01:49:28.060
is come up with a communication
strategy-- what your brand is,

01:49:28.060 --> 01:49:30.200
what you want to stand
for, the kind of articles

01:49:30.200 --> 01:49:33.250
and things you're going to
put out there-- and realize it

01:49:33.250 --> 01:49:36.788
doesn't matter if your
competitor sees them too.

01:49:36.788 --> 01:49:37.704
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:49:42.105 --> 01:49:42.980
CATHERINE KAPUTA: OK.

01:49:42.980 --> 01:49:43.880
Oh, I see.

01:49:43.880 --> 01:49:46.140
I see.

01:49:46.140 --> 01:49:47.270
OK.

01:49:47.270 --> 01:49:49.350
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:49:49.350 --> 01:49:53.200
And I'm thinking of it less
from the content I share.

01:49:53.200 --> 01:49:56.280
I can figure that out
as far as, hey, this

01:49:56.280 --> 01:49:59.730
is an interesting
article for either,

01:49:59.730 --> 01:50:02.270
whether it's one of them
doing something well

01:50:02.270 --> 01:50:04.630
or one of them doing
something poorly, or whatever.

01:50:04.630 --> 01:50:06.510
But more like
managing connections,

01:50:06.510 --> 01:50:09.087
like to Tom's points
earlier about Microsoft

01:50:09.087 --> 01:50:11.670
being a competitor of ours, now
I'm talking more to the people

01:50:11.670 --> 01:50:14.560
that I'm trying to engage
with and connect with.

01:50:14.560 --> 01:50:18.700
I don't necessarily
want CIO at Staples

01:50:18.700 --> 01:50:22.930
to also know that I'm having
active conversations with CMO

01:50:22.930 --> 01:50:29.170
at Office Depot or somebody
at Walmart or somebody else.

01:50:29.170 --> 01:50:32.220
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Yeah,
but you can on Settings

01:50:32.220 --> 01:50:37.460
disable letting people
know certain things,

01:50:37.460 --> 01:50:41.670
if you want, like
connections that you make.

01:50:41.670 --> 01:50:45.815
You can eliminate some of
that from the Notifications.

01:50:45.815 --> 01:50:46.440
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:50:46.440 --> 01:50:47.981
CATHERINE KAPUTA:
So you can do that.

01:50:50.270 --> 01:50:52.960
I don't know what else--
any other ideas here?

01:50:52.960 --> 01:50:53.876
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:51:05.120 --> 01:51:06.940
AUDIENCE: Well,
because many of them

01:51:06.940 --> 01:51:12.270
are insanely sensitive
to each other

01:51:12.270 --> 01:51:15.760
and what the other one's
doing or not doing.

01:51:15.760 --> 01:51:18.930
It's like everybody's scared
of-- so Lowe's and Walmart,

01:51:18.930 --> 01:51:20.995
not direct competitors,
but they kind of

01:51:20.995 --> 01:51:22.620
are watching what
each other are doing.

01:51:22.620 --> 01:51:28.080
And I don't go out and
advertise that I'm actively

01:51:28.080 --> 01:51:29.710
working with both of them.

01:51:29.710 --> 01:51:30.626
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:51:43.921 --> 01:51:45.670
AUDIENCE: It can work
both ways, I'm sure.

01:51:45.670 --> 01:51:46.660
CATHERINE KAPUTA: It
can work both ways.

01:51:46.660 --> 01:51:48.951
I'm just thinking too, when
I was a client perspective,

01:51:48.951 --> 01:51:52.865
there were a lot of people--
ad agencies, for example,

01:51:52.865 --> 01:51:54.240
can't have a
competitive account.

01:51:54.240 --> 01:51:55.220
AUDIENCE: Right.

01:51:55.220 --> 01:51:57.510
CATHERINE KAPUTA: So if
you're in an ad agency,

01:51:57.510 --> 01:52:00.160
they're not going to handle
any of my competitors.

01:52:00.160 --> 01:52:02.540
But there were other supplies
we dealt with, obviously,

01:52:02.540 --> 01:52:06.920
that are meeting with-- but
I think it's changing a lot,

01:52:06.920 --> 01:52:11.270
because I think historically
a lot of executives--

01:52:11.270 --> 01:52:15.140
and I would never mention
it in a meeting, obviously.

01:52:15.140 --> 01:52:16.600
You've got to downplay it.

01:52:16.600 --> 01:52:19.020
But I don't think you can
worry about it too much.

01:52:19.020 --> 01:52:22.584
You can eliminate certain
things from your Settings.

01:52:22.584 --> 01:52:24.334
AUDIENCE: It just
becomes a full-time job.

01:52:24.334 --> 01:52:25.961
It's like Facebook, right?

01:52:25.961 --> 01:52:26.960
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

01:52:26.960 --> 01:52:29.440
AUDIENCE: You can say, oh, you
can go put friends in groups--

01:52:29.440 --> 01:52:30.260
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

01:52:30.260 --> 01:52:30.920
Right.

01:52:30.920 --> 01:52:31.836
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:52:40.500 --> 01:52:41.620
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

01:52:41.620 --> 01:52:45.360
Right

01:52:45.360 --> 01:52:47.640
AUDIENCE: --the idea of brand.

01:52:47.640 --> 01:52:52.150
Because if your brand is such
that you are really an ultra

01:52:52.150 --> 01:52:54.060
connector and you're
using this as a tool

01:52:54.060 --> 01:52:56.970
and it's really--
because if you only

01:52:56.970 --> 01:52:59.370
have a couple of connections
and they're competitors

01:52:59.370 --> 01:53:00.970
with each other,
that feel sensitive,

01:53:00.970 --> 01:53:05.230
like you're choosing those two
companies, versus if you're

01:53:05.230 --> 01:53:09.280
really active in a very
specific way where it's

01:53:09.280 --> 01:53:12.610
your brand, whether it's the
maverick or the other things.

01:53:12.610 --> 01:53:15.440
I think that can lend itself
so that when someone sees it

01:53:15.440 --> 01:53:17.470
and they see that, oh,
he's connecting there too

01:53:17.470 --> 01:53:19.310
or he's in this group
that they're in,

01:53:19.310 --> 01:53:22.260
then it feels more authentic,
like, hey, look, this is me.

01:53:22.260 --> 01:53:23.710
I do this socially.

01:53:23.710 --> 01:53:27.540
You need to make it so that
that is your brand so that it

01:53:27.540 --> 01:53:30.050
doesn't feel like you're
sharing secrets across.

01:53:30.050 --> 01:53:33.210
It's more I share all
this stuff publicly.

01:53:33.210 --> 01:53:36.120
For me, I want to try to
get this where it is public

01:53:36.120 --> 01:53:38.530
that I-- if you want to
see that I'm connecting

01:53:38.530 --> 01:53:40.790
with new people, great, see it.

01:53:40.790 --> 01:53:42.400
Know that the
information is public.

01:53:42.400 --> 01:53:44.816
Because the other thing is
that even if you change privacy

01:53:44.816 --> 01:53:47.560
settings, we all know that
privacy settings change really

01:53:47.560 --> 01:53:48.060
frequently.

01:53:48.060 --> 01:53:50.450
So if you put
information out there,

01:53:50.450 --> 01:53:54.050
know that it is in the public
domain the moment it gets out.

01:53:54.050 --> 01:53:55.050
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

01:53:55.050 --> 01:53:56.800
I think it's a
whole new world now,

01:53:56.800 --> 01:53:59.320
and I think this is
part of doing business

01:53:59.320 --> 01:54:00.320
in the modern world.

01:54:04.590 --> 01:54:06.400
You've already got
Google brand behind you.

01:54:06.400 --> 01:54:07.860
That's very, very powerful.

01:54:07.860 --> 01:54:10.050
You want to build a strong
enough brand that they

01:54:10.050 --> 01:54:12.660
want to work with
you and they feel

01:54:12.660 --> 01:54:14.520
that they're getting
the attention from you,

01:54:14.520 --> 01:54:17.900
that they're getting your
smarts and your unique selling

01:54:17.900 --> 01:54:21.716
proposition, however
you've defined that.

01:54:21.716 --> 01:54:23.590
And I think that's what
it's all about today.

01:54:23.590 --> 01:54:26.540
Because I think people want
to work with the best talent

01:54:26.540 --> 01:54:30.650
that they feel comfortable
with, that they feel they get

01:54:30.650 --> 01:54:33.790
outstanding service
from, et cetera.

01:54:33.790 --> 01:54:34.670
Any other thoughts?

01:54:42.175 --> 01:54:44.800
Has anyone had an experience or
have you had an experience with

01:54:44.800 --> 01:54:48.096
a client saying, I don't like
that you're-- how do you handle

01:54:48.096 --> 01:54:48.870
that?

01:54:48.870 --> 01:54:50.536
AUDIENCE: What I was
going to go back to

01:54:50.536 --> 01:54:54.730
is at a higher level separating
you are your persona at Google,

01:54:54.730 --> 01:54:57.340
and then you're
outside of Google.

01:54:57.340 --> 01:55:00.950
We're trained, there's
a lot of things

01:55:00.950 --> 01:55:04.230
that we know that are
internal to our company.

01:55:04.230 --> 01:55:06.190
So you also have to be
very careful with when

01:55:06.190 --> 01:55:09.600
you go posting stuff and what
you're putting out there,

01:55:09.600 --> 01:55:11.450
it's outside of the company.

01:55:11.450 --> 01:55:14.580
And I think that maybe there
hasn't been enough thought

01:55:14.580 --> 01:55:17.610
given to the internal
versus the external

01:55:17.610 --> 01:55:19.070
and then how you
bridge that gap.

01:55:19.070 --> 01:55:20.940
And I've struggled
with that too.

01:55:20.940 --> 01:55:23.990
Because just like if you
have two competitors, how

01:55:23.990 --> 01:55:26.290
do you share information
in the right way,

01:55:26.290 --> 01:55:28.410
you can also share
too much out there,

01:55:28.410 --> 01:55:30.050
and you can have challenges.

01:55:30.050 --> 01:55:32.650
So you just have to give it a
lot of thought and make sure

01:55:32.650 --> 01:55:33.790
that it's--

01:55:33.790 --> 01:55:35.165
CATHERINE KAPUTA:
Can you give us

01:55:35.165 --> 01:55:38.080
an example of the decision
making in what you shared?

01:55:38.080 --> 01:55:45.190
AUDIENCE: When I was dealing
with GE in a past life,

01:55:45.190 --> 01:55:48.430
GE is ultra worried
about any information

01:55:48.430 --> 01:55:49.990
about them being shared.

01:55:49.990 --> 01:55:52.430
And we were talking to
Beth Comstock, the lady who

01:55:52.430 --> 01:55:55.080
you had up there, the
CMO of General Electric,

01:55:55.080 --> 01:55:59.460
and she came back-- she's
very much into social media--

01:55:59.460 --> 01:56:01.140
to one of my colleagues.

01:56:01.140 --> 01:56:04.220
She said that's actually
an internal GE thing.

01:56:04.220 --> 01:56:07.000
We don't want that spoken
about in the social.

01:56:07.000 --> 01:56:09.940
And she called LinkedIn
and had it taken down.

01:56:09.940 --> 01:56:14.052
So it was a big deal, and our
team got chastised for it.

01:56:14.052 --> 01:56:15.510
So you do need to
be a little bit--

01:56:15.510 --> 01:56:16.400
CATHERINE KAPUTA: You
need to be very careful

01:56:16.400 --> 01:56:18.140
with clients about
things like that.

01:56:18.140 --> 01:56:19.050
What can we say?

01:56:19.050 --> 01:56:20.680
Make sure they've
seen it before.

01:56:20.680 --> 01:56:24.420
Hey, I'm going to post this,
and are you comfortable with it?

01:56:24.420 --> 01:56:27.339
Because a lot of cultures
are like a GE culture.

01:56:27.339 --> 01:56:29.630
It's more traditional, and
they're very, very concerned

01:56:29.630 --> 01:56:31.420
about proprietary information.

01:56:31.420 --> 01:56:36.220
But part of your job is we value
that your information's private

01:56:36.220 --> 01:56:40.300
and the trust, the
trusted adviser.

01:56:40.300 --> 01:56:42.420
AUDIENCE: One of the
questions I have is just

01:56:42.420 --> 01:56:43.250
taking a step back.

01:56:43.250 --> 01:56:45.416
So I understand the importance
of getting your brand

01:56:45.416 --> 01:56:46.047
out there.

01:56:46.047 --> 01:56:47.630
Also, the two years
before I was here,

01:56:47.630 --> 01:56:49.129
I was doing social
media management.

01:56:49.129 --> 01:56:51.750
And we went from 300 likes to
3 million likes on Facebook,

01:56:51.750 --> 01:56:52.590
right?

01:56:52.590 --> 01:56:54.680
And my boss was
always, OK, great.

01:56:54.680 --> 01:56:55.930
How is this making us money?

01:56:55.930 --> 01:56:57.140
How is this
translating into sales?

01:56:57.140 --> 01:56:58.730
I'm like, but we
have so many likes.

01:56:58.730 --> 01:57:02.597
The question is, what sort of--

01:57:02.597 --> 01:57:04.930
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Well, that's
why I was showing the IBM

01:57:04.930 --> 01:57:06.380
story with the tracking page.

01:57:06.380 --> 01:57:08.850
AUDIENCE: Right.

01:57:08.850 --> 01:57:12.850
CATHERINE KAPUTA:
Social media is so new

01:57:12.850 --> 01:57:16.214
that a key measurement is
this whole idea of engagement.

01:57:16.214 --> 01:57:17.630
And how do you
measure engagement?

01:57:20.680 --> 01:57:23.430
And it's a thorny problem
in the whole branding world.

01:57:23.430 --> 01:57:24.530
How do you measure that?

01:57:24.530 --> 01:57:26.850
But the big thing that
people are trying to do now

01:57:26.850 --> 01:57:29.710
is link it with a
landing page so they

01:57:29.710 --> 01:57:33.480
can track new leads, what
kind of communications

01:57:33.480 --> 01:57:35.990
they're giving to
that potential lead,

01:57:35.990 --> 01:57:38.790
and then tracking conversion
that it became a client.

01:57:38.790 --> 01:57:41.550
Now then there's the
question of existing clients.

01:57:41.550 --> 01:57:45.080
Again, it's this whole idea if
you believe the whole branding

01:57:45.080 --> 01:57:50.120
bible that you want to have
meaningful touchpoints,

01:57:50.120 --> 01:57:54.220
and you want to have
consistent, ongoing touchpoints.

01:57:54.220 --> 01:57:56.550
And there's a lot of
reasons advertisers

01:57:56.550 --> 01:58:00.090
feel this is valuable, so that
everything you communicate

01:58:00.090 --> 01:58:06.590
to the client is on-brand and
on-strategy and consistent

01:58:06.590 --> 01:58:09.190
and that it's ongoing, that
you keep the relation--

01:58:09.190 --> 01:58:12.930
and it's a way of augmenting
the personal relationship,

01:58:12.930 --> 01:58:16.890
how many times you call
the client or prospect.

01:58:16.890 --> 01:58:19.030
But the thing that
they're trying to do

01:58:19.030 --> 01:58:20.580
is this whole tracking.

01:58:20.580 --> 01:58:22.180
It's a new area.

01:58:22.180 --> 01:58:25.620
And that's where they're trying
to get leads to a landing page,

01:58:25.620 --> 01:58:28.030
so then you contract conversion
and things like that.

01:58:28.030 --> 01:58:30.580
So that's how
you're making money.

01:58:30.580 --> 01:58:39.660
And I guess as I say, it's a
whole new area of branding.

01:58:39.660 --> 01:58:41.330
So it's this whole
thing of what are

01:58:41.330 --> 01:58:44.410
the other ways we can
measure the effectiveness?

01:58:44.410 --> 01:58:49.109
So it's in
development right now.

01:58:53.330 --> 01:58:55.570
AUDIENCE: I don't know
how to speak into these.

01:58:55.570 --> 01:58:56.364
OK.

01:58:56.364 --> 01:58:58.640
CATHERINE KAPUTA:
That's working.

01:58:58.640 --> 01:59:00.440
AUDIENCE: I think
that also goes back

01:59:00.440 --> 01:59:05.910
to what Ketan was saying
with campaigning and emails.

01:59:05.910 --> 01:59:09.360
Once we've done all of this
and we've established ourselves

01:59:09.360 --> 01:59:12.130
on LinkedIn, whether
or not Erin thinks

01:59:12.130 --> 01:59:18.900
we have credible profiles,
but as long as prospects do,

01:59:18.900 --> 01:59:21.840
Kira and I found that
we could use InMails

01:59:21.840 --> 01:59:24.560
as a way to establish
the relationship

01:59:24.560 --> 01:59:29.355
and set up a meeting and kind of
nurture that and go from there.

01:59:29.355 --> 01:59:31.670
I don't want to say too much.

01:59:31.670 --> 01:59:35.020
We're doing a presentation on
it to a few people in this room,

01:59:35.020 --> 01:59:38.684
so I don't want to
speak too much on it.

01:59:38.684 --> 01:59:41.100
CATHERINE KAPUTA: How were you
tracking the effectiveness?

01:59:44.440 --> 01:59:47.360
Can you not destroy
your presentation

01:59:47.360 --> 01:59:49.814
but give us some insight?

01:59:49.814 --> 01:59:51.480
AUDIENCE: Well, of
course we're tracking

01:59:51.480 --> 01:59:54.170
response rates and
the amount of meetings

01:59:54.170 --> 01:59:57.610
that we set from the
outreach that we do

01:59:57.610 --> 02:00:00.790
and then also tracking
how the connections change

02:00:00.790 --> 02:00:04.180
from third-degree
to then first-degree

02:00:04.180 --> 02:00:07.360
after sending one InMail.

02:00:07.360 --> 02:00:11.420
And also it's been successful
connecting with people

02:00:11.420 --> 02:00:14.530
that we've talked to in
the past, other prospects,

02:00:14.530 --> 02:00:15.960
going out, connecting
with those,

02:00:15.960 --> 02:00:19.490
and then seeing-- many of us
work within regions, right?

02:00:19.490 --> 02:00:22.910
So if you're connected with
this many CIOs in your region,

02:00:22.910 --> 02:00:26.800
it makes it easier to
send an InMail to a CIO

02:00:26.800 --> 02:00:30.400
also in that region who perhaps
is connected to those two

02:00:30.400 --> 02:00:31.940
you're already connected with.

02:00:31.940 --> 02:00:34.780
So just kind of increasing
your credibility

02:00:34.780 --> 02:00:36.822
through the connections
that you have has helped.

02:00:36.822 --> 02:00:37.821
CATHERINE KAPUTA: Right.

02:00:37.821 --> 02:00:38.341
Right.

02:00:38.341 --> 02:00:38.840
Yeah.

02:00:38.840 --> 02:00:41.040
And this also
gives you a vehicle

02:00:41.040 --> 02:00:44.800
for ongoing communication.

02:00:44.800 --> 02:00:46.260
So that's what
really starts making

02:00:46.260 --> 02:00:51.330
a difference-- we talked
about being on-trend.

02:00:51.330 --> 02:00:53.580
We talked about being
up-to-date-- figuring out

02:00:53.580 --> 02:00:55.790
what's of interest and
periodically sending things

02:00:55.790 --> 02:00:57.960
so that there's these
touches going on.

02:00:57.960 --> 02:01:01.240
When you think of brands
that you do business with,

02:01:01.240 --> 02:01:02.800
they'll send follow-up emails.

02:01:02.800 --> 02:01:04.734
Then you'll get
something after that.

02:01:04.734 --> 02:01:06.400
Thought you might be
interested in this.

02:01:06.400 --> 02:01:08.210
So you want to do
a similar thing.

02:01:08.210 --> 02:01:13.910
That's what eventually works
and keeps a relationship,

02:01:13.910 --> 02:01:16.954
augments the kind of personal
touch that you can give.

02:01:19.670 --> 02:01:20.170
All right.

02:01:20.170 --> 02:01:22.582
So we were giving
the little gifts.

02:01:22.582 --> 02:01:24.790
I know you're going to have
a presentation after this

02:01:24.790 --> 02:01:28.340
on story, but you always
want to be telling stories.

02:01:28.340 --> 02:01:32.170
Stories are sticky and
disguise the sales message.

02:01:32.170 --> 02:01:37.290
And this is a whole big
message of branding.

02:01:37.290 --> 02:01:40.140
You rarely see a commercial
that talks about really

02:01:40.140 --> 02:01:44.040
what the product is and analyzes
it in any kind of rational way.

02:01:44.040 --> 02:01:47.110
Really they wrap the
brands in stories.

02:01:47.110 --> 02:01:49.890
They tell stories that
people connect with.

02:01:49.890 --> 02:01:53.250
And you want to use stories
to tell about here's

02:01:53.250 --> 02:01:55.340
a project that we
had from a client.

02:01:55.340 --> 02:01:57.570
Here was the challenge.

02:01:57.570 --> 02:01:58.630
And then tell a story.

02:01:58.630 --> 02:02:02.120
And the best stories are
stories you can film.

02:02:02.120 --> 02:02:05.230
You want to bring to life
so that people can imagine

02:02:05.230 --> 02:02:09.390
they were there and the
challenges, the obstacles.

02:02:09.390 --> 02:02:12.660
There's a lot of
different story formats.

02:02:12.660 --> 02:02:15.580
The story format that I used
when I was telling that Barbara

02:02:15.580 --> 02:02:18.580
Corcoran story in the beginning,
I could have just made

02:02:18.580 --> 02:02:22.590
one slide and said here
are seven principles

02:02:22.590 --> 02:02:24.830
that Barbara Corcoran displayed.

02:02:24.830 --> 02:02:28.270
But no, I told the story
about her boyfriend

02:02:28.270 --> 02:02:30.690
left her and this and
that and the other thing

02:02:30.690 --> 02:02:34.320
and she wrote "The Corcoran
Report" and the Donald Trump

02:02:34.320 --> 02:02:35.640
thing.

02:02:35.640 --> 02:02:37.210
You want to build
it so people get

02:02:37.210 --> 02:02:41.370
a sense of the different phases,
the struggle, the obstacles

02:02:41.370 --> 02:02:43.631
and then how you solved
the problem at the end.

02:02:43.631 --> 02:02:45.880
So you want to sort of bring
that whole thing to life.

02:02:45.880 --> 02:02:50.840
And LinkedIn gives you a lot
of avenues with the updates,

02:02:50.840 --> 02:02:52.910
so anybody can post an update.

02:02:52.910 --> 02:02:54.750
You can do it in Groups.

02:02:54.750 --> 02:02:58.170
You can make it anonymous,
a technology client

02:02:58.170 --> 02:03:01.930
or a retail client, so not
mention a specific name,

02:03:01.930 --> 02:03:02.640
if you want.

02:03:02.640 --> 02:03:06.870
But tell a story that's related
to problems they're probably

02:03:06.870 --> 02:03:12.070
facing and how it was solved
it how it was successful.

02:03:12.070 --> 02:03:13.880
You always want to
be asking questions.

02:03:13.880 --> 02:03:18.240
Questions are a very powerful
thing in advertising.

02:03:18.240 --> 02:03:22.840
Because statements are
passive, but a question

02:03:22.840 --> 02:03:24.470
begs involvement.

02:03:24.470 --> 02:03:27.050
Ronald Reagan famously
asked the question

02:03:27.050 --> 02:03:30.220
are you better off today
than you were four years ago.

02:03:30.220 --> 02:03:35.760
Most people couldn't say
yes, and he got elected.

02:03:35.760 --> 02:03:37.730
Questions can be
very provocative,

02:03:37.730 --> 02:03:41.810
because it gets people thinking,
just like the story gets people

02:03:41.810 --> 02:03:45.390
thinking about the story
and gets people all involved

02:03:45.390 --> 02:03:47.420
in the story.

02:03:47.420 --> 02:03:48.960
Questions get people involved.

02:03:48.960 --> 02:03:53.250
When you just make
statements, we did this,

02:03:53.250 --> 02:03:57.310
it doesn't really retain
in the memory the same way.

02:03:57.310 --> 02:03:59.820
You always want to
be tracking contacts.

02:03:59.820 --> 02:04:00.991
And LinkedIn has a tool.

02:04:00.991 --> 02:04:02.990
I don't know if a lot of
people know about this,

02:04:02.990 --> 02:04:06.260
but you can track
relationships or you

02:04:06.260 --> 02:04:10.640
can make notes,
reminders, how you met.

02:04:10.640 --> 02:04:13.000
You can tag them, put
different tags on people.

02:04:13.000 --> 02:04:15.030
So you can go to
LinkedIn and bring up

02:04:15.030 --> 02:04:16.910
all the people
with a similar tag.

02:04:16.910 --> 02:04:21.540
Or you can transfer
your first-degree names

02:04:21.540 --> 02:04:26.440
to a CRM system that you use
and like better to manage them.

02:04:26.440 --> 02:04:29.960
But you want to be tracking
all these contacts.

02:04:29.960 --> 02:04:31.870
And as I mentioned
earlier, branders

02:04:31.870 --> 02:04:38.030
think of increasing
touchpoints, online, offline.

02:04:38.030 --> 02:04:42.120
You want to leverage
your status updates.

02:04:42.120 --> 02:04:43.470
We talked about repurposing.

02:04:43.470 --> 02:04:47.070
You can make it public
plus Twitter, so anything

02:04:47.070 --> 02:04:49.620
you update that it goes out
to the public plus Twitter

02:04:49.620 --> 02:04:51.130
automatically.

02:04:51.130 --> 02:04:56.260
You can also tag your
updates in the body of it,

02:04:56.260 --> 02:04:59.350
@company or @user, user,
and it'll automatically

02:04:59.350 --> 02:05:00.480
go to them as well.

02:05:00.480 --> 02:05:02.880
If you have certain
clients or prospects

02:05:02.880 --> 02:05:05.540
that you have permission
to use their name,

02:05:05.540 --> 02:05:10.510
it's an easy way to keep
that touch going on.

02:05:10.510 --> 02:05:12.900
And I think it's important
to-- how can you do all this

02:05:12.900 --> 02:05:14.390
and keep your day job too?

02:05:14.390 --> 02:05:17.820
So you always want
to be automating.

02:05:17.820 --> 02:05:20.620
I see LinkedIn as the
center because there's

02:05:20.620 --> 02:05:23.140
280 million members and growing.

02:05:23.140 --> 02:05:26.010
It's the business site.

02:05:26.010 --> 02:05:28.670
But leverage all
these other vehicles

02:05:28.670 --> 02:05:30.290
that you have as well too.

02:05:30.290 --> 02:05:34.520
G+ is good for Circles and
people that share similar

02:05:34.520 --> 02:05:36.130
passions and interests.

02:05:36.130 --> 02:05:41.920
Twitter I see as like a PR
thing, very short sentences.

02:05:41.920 --> 02:05:45.000
You can link, as you know,
to other longer articles.

02:05:45.000 --> 02:05:47.610
But it's a very
quick form of PR.

02:05:47.610 --> 02:05:49.340
YouTube, videos.

02:05:49.340 --> 02:05:51.000
Videos are very powerful.

02:05:51.000 --> 02:05:54.370
Facebook, Pinterest
is about pinning.

02:05:54.370 --> 02:05:58.370
I have a business where
it's not so visible.

02:05:58.370 --> 02:06:00.950
But I have certain
slogans that I use.

02:06:00.950 --> 02:06:03.430
If you don't brand
yourself, other people will.

02:06:03.430 --> 02:06:06.785
But I put with an interesting
visual and put it on Pinterest.

02:06:09.640 --> 02:06:12.572
So you always want to be
moving the brand forward.

02:06:12.572 --> 02:06:13.530
You want to be current.

02:06:13.530 --> 02:06:15.250
You want to be meaningful.

02:06:15.250 --> 02:06:17.980
Multimedia, figure out the
different media you can use.

02:06:17.980 --> 02:06:21.220
Consistent, ongoing,
and this whole idea

02:06:21.220 --> 02:06:24.940
of having an
emotional connection.

02:06:24.940 --> 02:06:27.550
And my final thought is you
always want to be visible.

02:06:27.550 --> 02:06:30.210
Branding is always about
building visibility.

02:06:30.210 --> 02:06:33.750
Social selling is about
building visibility, finding

02:06:33.750 --> 02:06:36.740
the right people,
connecting with them,

02:06:36.740 --> 02:06:38.410
building relationships.

02:06:38.410 --> 02:06:41.160
And just like we talked about
there's a beauty premium,

02:06:41.160 --> 02:06:44.160
there's a visibility
premium, both for products

02:06:44.160 --> 02:06:45.490
and for people.

02:06:45.490 --> 02:06:48.440
And people who are
visible, research

02:06:48.440 --> 02:06:51.340
shows people think
they're better than people

02:06:51.340 --> 02:06:53.300
who aren't that visible
in the industry.

02:06:53.300 --> 02:06:56.840
And LinkedIn gives you a
vehicle for building visibility

02:06:56.840 --> 02:07:01.080
and building connections with
your clients and prospects.

